INSERT INTO `messages` (`id`, `message_key`, `content_id`, `content_type`, `language`, `content`, `length`, `order`, `tags`, `modified_by`, `created_at`, `updated_at`) VALUES
(1, 'fyl-sms-en-1', 2, 'sms', 'English', 'The first PNC visits are very important.  If for any reason you gave birth outside of a medical facility, you need to attend PNC within 24 hours of giving birth. Even if you feel fine and your baby seems well it is important to go. Because of the amount of blood lost during delivery you can become anemic or have very low blood. You will be given a dose of Vitamin A, and another one when you go to the PNC visit 2 days after the birth which will help raise your blood levels.  Your baby will be weighed, measured and get their first immunizations which are very important to protect your baby against Polio and TB.  You can also register your baby for a birth certificate at this time. It is best to go to PNC two times during the first week of your baby?s life and again when your baby is 6 weeks old. If you haven?t been yet be sure to go this week. Chord care: When your baby is born, the  umbilical chord is cut freeing you from your baby. Once the chord is cut there is a wound where the chord was cut that looks like a tree stump. Keep this wound dry and clean. Don''t put anything on it like  soap, traditional herbs, shea butter or even surgical spirit. Make sure that baby napkins don''t rub or cover the wound. Don''t force the stump of the chord to fall off as it will fall by itself in 10-12 days. Infections of the stump can cause death. See a doctor straight away if there is bleeding from the chord, or if you see any redness or pus around it.', 1457, 1, '1st PNC', 1, '2014-06-24 00:50:22', '2014-07-06 16:18:35'),
(2, 'fyl-sms-en-2', 2, 'sms', 'English', 'By now your baby?s umbilical cord stump should be dry and may have fallen already. If you see any puss or redness at the area take your baby to clinic right away as infections can be dangerous to your new baby. Also, every baby has a soft spot on the top of his or her head where the bones have not yet sealed giving your baby''s brain room to grow. It will start to close by itself at about 6 months.This soft spot is not an ulcer and you should not put hot compresses or any herbal medicines on it. The spot should be flat or raised a bit when you feel it. If the spot has sunk down and it feels like a hole you must go to the clinic as your baby is not well.  Do not try to shape your baby''s head as this is dangerous and can cause serious damage to your little one''s brain.  ', 778, 2, 'Fontenelle/ Cord Care', 1, '2014-06-24 00:50:22', '2014-07-06 16:18:35'),
(3, 'fyl-sms-en-3', 2, 'sms', 'English', 'Breast-fed babies are healthier, stronger and suffer fewer sicknesses than babies that are fed other foods or drinks. Breast-milk alone 8 - 12 times a day, is all baby needs to eat for the first 6 months of life.  Breast milk contains water so your baby doesn?t need to be given water. The right positioning during feeding is important for your baby to eat well.  Your baby''s whole body should be turned to face you, and you and your baby should be belly to belly. Signs that your baby is feeding well are: baby''s chin is touching your breast, more of the dark skin around your nipple can be seen above your baby''s mouth than below it, your baby takes long, deep sucks, and you don''t feel any pain in the nipple. Both of your breasts should feel empty when your baby is finished. If you are worried that your baby is not getting enough to eat, don''t be afraid to ask your midwife. They can help you so that you are sure that your little one gets all they need to grow healthy and strong. ', 988, 3, 'EBF', 1, '2014-06-24 00:50:22', '2014-07-06 16:18:35'),
(4, 'fyl-sms-en-4', 2, 'sms', 'English', 'Malaria is very dangerous to a newborn baby and is caused by the bite of mosquitos. Be sure that  you and your baby sleep under an insecticide treated mosquito net. Be sure that evening time and early dawn your baby is protected from mosquitos by dressing them in something light that covers their legs, feet and arms. Remember to keep your room mosquito free with sprays or by burning coils.  Also clearing bushes around the house, and covering water containers will help control mosquitos. If baby has a fever, is not interested in eating, not sucking well, or spitting up with force, or their eyes or skin look yellow, do not wait to take them to the clinic. Early treatment can save your baby''s life.', 704, 4, 'Malaria', 1, '2014-06-24 00:50:22', '2014-07-06 16:18:35'),
(5, 'fyl-sms-en-5', 2, 'sms', 'English', 'Good hand washing practices can prevent the spread of diseases such as polio, rotovirus, typhoid and cholera and eye infections.  It is always important to keep your home environment clean, but the best way to keep germs from causing a problem for your baby is by washing your hands. Wash your hands with soap and clean water, rubbing them well to remove the germs.  Always wash your hands before handling your newborn, and after changing your baby''s nappies.  And of course, wash hands after toileting, after handling raw food and always before cooking or eating. Don''t be afraid to ask others to wash their hands before holding or touching  your new baby as well. We can''t protect babies from everything that might make them sick but hand washing is an important step to help keep your baby and the rest of your family healthy.', 829, 5, 'Infection Control/ hygiene', 1, '2014-06-24 01:05:34', '2014-07-06 16:18:35'),
(6, 'fyl-sms-en-6', 2, 'sms', 'English', 'Immunization gives the body protection from certain diseases.  An immunization tells the body to create antibodies which are like soldiers that fight off the disease. This week your baby needs to receive immunization against Tetanus/diphtheria/whooping cough (DPT), influenzaB(HiB), Hepatitis B, Polio, Rotavirus and Pneumonia, which are all dangerous diseases that can kill.  Immunizations are free at government facilities. Remember to always take your baby?s health card so the jabs can be recorded.  Immunizations are not harmful and can protect your baby from deadly diseases.  ', 583, 6, 'Immunization', 1, '2014-06-24 01:05:34', '2014-07-06 16:18:35'),
(7, 'fyl-sms-en-7', 2, 'sms', 'English', 'MEN: Your wife needs to report to PNC around now to make sure she is fine, after giving birth. One thing that should be talked about at PNC is contraception in order to space your children at least 2 years apart. Contraception methods are a personal choice for every couple and it gives your wife?s body enough time to fully recover before getting pregnant again. Using contraception is not so that your wife can be promiscuous or go outside of your marriage. Getting pregnant again too soon can put her life at risk, as her blood levels may still be low. She can also bleed  too much with the next delivery. While breastfeeding she may be protected from getting pregnant for some months,  but she can still get pregnant even if breastfeeding. Speak to your doctor about a contraception method that will work for you and your wife, take time to decide and start the method as soon as your wife is no longer exclusively breast feeding.', 934, 7, 'MEN: Contraception/Postnatal clinic', 1, '2014-06-24 01:05:34', '2014-07-06 16:18:35'),
(8, 'fyl-sms-en-8', 2, 'sms', 'English', 'Babies only know how to breath through their nose, so if the nose is stopped up your baby can''t breath.  A baby should not take more than 50 breaths in one minute. Watch your baby as they breathe.  If the lower part of the chest sinks in when the child takes a breath or if the belly is moving in and out when they breathe your baby is in trouble and needs to go to the clinic straight.  You can help prevent pneumonia by protecting your baby from sleeping directly under a fan, and from breathing in smoke. The smoke from tobacco, cooking fires, burning rubbish, and fires to clear land are all dangerous for your little ones growing lungs. If the doctor gives baby medicine to take make sure you understand the directions very well and follow them carefully.  Complete the whole course of medicine.  Be sure to continue breastfeeding. Breastmilk helps your baby get better quick and is the only food they require.  ', 917, 8, 'Pneumonia', 1, '2014-06-24 01:05:35', '2014-07-06 16:18:35'),
(9, 'fyl-sms-en-9', 2, 'sms', 'English', 'Your baby is growing very fast now and should put on almost 1kg a month. Your baby should also be getting stronger now, but you still need to support the head when carrying or when your baby is tied to your back.  If your baby is not getting stronger, not sucking well at the breast, is coughing with force, vomiting, or has difficulty breathing you must report to the clinic straight. It is a sign that your baby is not well. If your baby seems weak, eyes are sunken or the fontanelle feels like a hole, your baby needs proper medical attention. Keep up with breastfeeding and remember you don?t need to give any other food or liquid, even if  baby seems hungry.  The more you breastfeed the more milk your body will make so your baby will always get enough.  ', 761, 9, 'milestones/ danger signs', 1, '2014-06-24 01:05:35', '2014-07-06 16:18:35'),
(10, 'fyl-sms-en-10', 2, 'sms', 'English', 'This week your baby needs another immunization injection to protect them from the childhood killer diseases. Immunizations are free at government facilities and going to the clinic gives you a chance to ask any questions you may have about how your baby is doing.  If you are having any problems breastfeeding now is the time to speak to the doctor. Your baby should still be drinking only breastmilk as it gives baby everything they need to grow strong and healthy.  Even if it is hot outside, your baby doesn''t need water, as breastmilk contains water.  Do not start giving solid foods. Your baby''s belly is not ready to digest solid foods and feeding solids before 6 months of age, causes serious belly problems and diarrhoea. Breastmilk alone is the best and only food your baby should eat until 6 months of age.', 816, 10, 'Immunization/EBF', 1, '2014-06-24 01:05:35', '2014-07-06 16:18:35'),
(11, 'fyl-sms-en-11', 2, 'sms', 'English', 'IF your are exclusively breast feeding which means feeding every four hours or more often through the day as well as night time feeds, and your period has not returned, you are protected from getting pregnant at this time, but it is not too early to start thinking about using contraceptives.  If you are not exclusively breast feeding on demand, you''ll begin to ovulate before you have a period and you risk getting pregnant again too soon.  Discuss birth spacing and contraceptives with your husband and speak to your midwife to find a method that will work for both of you. Remember that breast feeding is all your baby needs to stay healthy and grow well for the first 6 months of life, so continue breastfeeding exclusively to protect yourself from getting pregnant as well as giving your baby the best chance at staying healthy. ', 835, 11, 'Contraception/EBF/LAM', 1, '2014-06-24 01:05:35', '2014-07-06 16:18:35'),
(12, 'fyl-sms-en-12', 2, 'sms', 'English', 'In hot weather babies can overheat easily which is dangerous.  If you aren''t sure whether your child is overheated, touch the skin. Damp hot skin is a sign that they are too warm.  Keep your child cooler by dressing them in loose, light, cotton clothing, and use a cotton hat instead of a wooly one.   To keep your child cooler at night, make sure your mattress is firm and your baby only has a light covering. If you are warm so is your baby. You can cool down a hot or feverish baby by wiping his bare body with a face cloth soaked in cool water. Cooling your baby makes sure they don?t become dehydrated or suffer heat stroke or heat exhaustion. Breastfeeding day and night also keeps baby hydrated and cooler."When your baby is sleeping in the bed with you, make sure your mattress is firm: Your baby could suffocate or overheat if sleeping on a soft mattress. If your bed has a frame, a headboard or is against a wall, make sure the mattress fits tight with the edges of the bed so that there is no risk of your baby falling into the gap. This risk is biggest for for three to 10-month-olds. Your baby only needs a light covering at night.  If you are feeling warm enough then so is your baby. Finally to protect against malaria your baby must sleep under an insecticide treated mosquito net. Most 10-week-old babies still wake up in the middle of the night to eat. When baby wakes up in the night you still need to give them breastmilk as it is important to help them grow.', 1479, 12, 'heat/clothing', 1, '2014-06-24 01:05:35', '2014-07-06 16:18:35'),
(13, 'fyl-sms-en-13', 2, 'sms', 'English', 'Your baby is probably showing signs that they want to eat real food. They are learning to copy you as you eat, as well as learning to reach out and pick things.  Just because they can reach and pick up the food does not mean that the belly is ready to manage the food.  Resist the feeling that your baby needs to eat solid food.  If your baby is gaining weight, looks healthy and seems happy after breastfeeds, then you can feel sure they are getting what they need. If your baby is making 6-8 wet nappies in a day and faeces is soft and yellowish then your baby is eating enough. If your baby takes to the breast quickly and eats well without slipping off, crying or falling asleep then they are eating well. If your baby is taking a good mouthful of the breast, sucking and swallowing without causing you pain then your baby is doing well.  If you have any questions don''t be afraid to ask a doctor or nurse for help. Remember that breastmilk  is all your baby needs until six months of age. Giving any other foods or water can cause diarrhoea and serious belly problems for your baby.', 1087, 13, 'EBF', 1, '2014-06-24 01:05:35', '2014-07-06 16:18:35'),
(14, 'fyl-sms-en-14', 2, 'sms', 'English', 'MEN: This week your baby needs another immunization to protect them from the childhood killer diseases. Immunizations are free at the government facilities. Even though it may seem like a long wait to see the nurse or doctor, it is a small price to pay in order to keep your baby healthy. Your baby should still be drinking only breastmilk as it gives them everything they need to grow strong and healthy. Your wife will continue to make enough breastmilk as long as she continues to breastfeed regularly and is eating well.  After the injection your baby may cry a lot or show a small rash. Be sure your wife breastfeeds frequently to help your baby recover from the injection.  If  your baby is very warm (fever), vomiting with force, not breathing well or coughing with force it is a sign that baby is sick. Go to the clinic before it is too late.', 850, 14, 'Immunization /EBF/danger signs', 1, '2014-06-24 01:05:35', '2014-07-06 16:18:35'),
(15, 'fyl-sms-en-15', 2, 'sms', 'English', 'Diarrhoea kills babies by draining liquid from the body thus dehydrating the child. A child?s life is in danger if there are three or more watery stools in a day or if there is blood in the faeces.  Do not give your baby water, minerals, traditional medicines or herbs. These can make the sickness worse. Starting ORS at home while you are organizing to get your baby to the clinic can help save your baby?s life.  Get the ORS sachet at a pharmacy or chemical seller.  Pour one sachet into a clean bowl. Add 1 big beer bottle or 2 mineral bottles of clean water, mix well and give to your baby. Also, breastfeed often to help replace fluid lost in stools. Even if you have started treating your baby at home you still need to take your child to the clinic as soon as possible, so that the problem that caused the diarrhoea can be addressed. ', 841, 15, 'Diarrhoea/ EBF', 1, '2014-06-24 01:05:35', '2014-07-06 16:18:35'),
(16, 'fyl-sms-en-16', 2, 'sms', 'English', 'As your baby reaches 3 months old, you may feel tired from breast feeding, or think it takes too much time and energy to continue giving only breast milk. You may also worry that your baby will not take foods at 6 months because they will only like the breast.  Your baby will be healthier and stronger if you make the sacrifice of time and energy now for your child.  Taking care of a sick baby takes more time, energy and costs more money than if you continue with only breast milk. If you are busy working, you can express milk from the breast and it can be given to your baby from a clean cup. After 6 months you can slowly introduce soft foods that your child will enjoy because their body will be ready to cope with foods in additional to breast milk. Doing the best for your child now ensures they grow up well.', 818, 16, 'EBF', 1, '2014-06-24 01:05:35', '2014-07-06 16:18:35'),
(17, 'fyl-sms-en-17', 2, 'sms', 'English', 'Keeping your house environment clean and washing your hands keeps the whole family safe from diarrhoea and other sickness.  When changing nappies, all faeces should be disposed of in a latrine or toilet, or buried. If you have washed faeces off nappies in a bucket of water, the water should be thrown far away from the house, cooking areas, and away from where other children play. Always wash your hands with soap and water before feeding your child, after changing babies nappies, after toileting, before handling any food, cooking or eating. Babies now also like to put their own hands and anything they can grab into their mouth, so clean their hands often and watch that your baby doesn''t pick rubbish or anything else from the ground to put in their mouth. Don?t be afraid to share what you have learned about handwashing with others in your household. A clean house and clean hands will protect your new precious gift, and the whole family from sickness.  ', 964, 17, 'Handwashing for family', 1, '2014-06-24 01:06:30', '2014-07-06 16:18:35'),
(18, 'fyl-sms-en-18', 2, 'sms', 'English', ' Malaria is very dangerous for small babies and if not treated right away can cause death. Babies can not tell us when a mosquito is troubling them or they are being bit, so we must do everything possible to protect them from mosquito bites.  First, your baby must sleep under an insecticide treated mosquito net. Also, make sure that the room your baby sleeps in does not have hanging clothes.  Fold the clothes away so mosquitos have no place to hide. If you spray the room make sure that you spray at least 30 minutes before baby goes in the room, as the spray is not good for their lungs.  In the evening and early morning hours make sure that your baby is well covered  including feet and legs with light colored clothing to protect them.  Lastly, if your baby has a fever, is limp or weak, does not want to eat or vomits, has a fever or doesn''t seem well, take them to clinic straight away. If baby has fever, you must cool baby down by wiping them with a face cloth soaked in cool water while you are preparing to go to the clinic.  Malaria does not go away by itself and traditional medicines are not good for babies.  Understand how to give any medicines the doctor gives and give the full course. And as always, breastfeeding helps baby get better quick so be sure to feed and feed often.', 1298, 18, 'Malaria reminder', 1, '2014-06-24 01:06:30', '2014-07-06 16:18:35'),
(19, 'fyl-sms-en-19', 2, 'sms', 'English', 'MEN:  Even though your wife is still breastfeeding, she can now become pregnant again. It is time to discuss family planning and spacing of your children. Family planning methods affect each woman differently, but none of the methods make women go outside of their marriage. There are many choices when it comes to contraception or family planning, some which are short term and others that protect for a longer time.  Spacing children allows your wife?s body to fully recover before getting pregnant again, ensuring that she doesn?t bleed too much with the next pregnancy, and allows the family time to financially prepare for another child. Children are a gift from God, and planning when to have your next one makes sure that each child has the best chance at life. You can get more information by attending family planning counseling at the clinic with your wife, which will help you both make the best decision for your family. It?s time to start a method now. ', 966, 19, 'MEN: Family Planning', 1, '2014-06-24 01:06:30', '2014-07-06 16:18:35'),
(20, 'fyl-sms-en-20', 2, 'sms', 'English', 'Most cases of diahorrea sicknesses in babies comes giving your young baby foods other than breastmilk.  Food and water carry bacterias like typhoid and cholera. While an adult can usually recover from diahorrea your baby?s body is not strong enough to recover from diahorrea and can die.  Even if you feel your baby wants to eat foods other than breastmilk, their body is not ready to cope with bacteria?s that come along with foods.  Do not give Pap, Ewedu, fish, egg, baby foods, prawn, groundnuts or soyabeans, or any formulated foods like cerelac or semovita, pepper or gari water. Your baby will be healthier, stronger and protected from diahorrea sickness if you delay giving foods until after the first 6 months of their life."By now, your baby is growing faster and faster, and should be getting much stronger. If you place them on their belly, they may stretch their arms and legs out and bend the back. When placed on the back, they might lift their head and shoulders. Your baby may even sit up for a small time without your help. Make sure that where they are playing is safe and if possible put pillows around them for cushion if they fall over.  Let them play while laying on the belly on a clean mat on the ground. Lifting the head and chest up to see toys or your face helps make the neck muscles stronger and develops the head control needed for sitting up.  This month, use feeding time to cuddle, hold, and love your baby --  soon they will only want to wiggle away from you. For now clapping your hands for them or giving them something safe and clean to hold can be fun for your baby and helps them learn and grow. ', 1636, 20, 'No Solids', 1, '2014-06-24 01:06:30', '2014-07-06 16:18:35'),
(21, 'fyl-sms-en-21', 2, 'sms', 'English', 'Evil Spirits do not make your baby sick.  Malaria, diahorrea diseases, pneumonia and other fevers are all medical problems which require proper medical attention.  Traditional medicines and herbs are not good for a young baby. If baby has a fever, is not interested in eating, not sucking well at the breast, or spitting up with force, or their eyes or skin look yellow, do not wait to take them to the clinic. Also, if your baby is coughing, has trouble breathing, seems weak or overly sleepy there is something wrong. With a small baby it is difficult to know exactly  what is causing fever or weakness, so it is best to take your baby straight away to the clinic. Early treatment can save your baby''s life.', 709, 21, 'Warning signs', 1, '2014-06-24 01:06:30', '2014-07-06 16:18:35'),
(22, 'fyl-sms-en-22', 2, 'sms', 'English', 'Your period can come anytime from now.  Remember you will ovulate first and can get pregnant before you see your period again. Family planning gives you the choice of when to have your next child. Spacing your children allows you to give each of your children the time they deserve to grow well. It also gives your family time to financially prepare for more children. Taking a family planning method does not make you go outside of your marriage. And using a family planning method now does not cause you to be ill with your next pregnancy. Every woman responds differently to different methods like the pill, IUD, injections or condoms. If the first method you choose does not go well with you, don?t give up on finding a method that does. There are many choices that are safe while you are still breastfeeding and one will work well for you. Speak with your doctor or midwife to help you make the best choice.', 912, 22, 'Family Planning', 1, '2014-06-24 01:06:30', '2014-07-06 16:18:35'),
(23, 'fyl-sms-en-23', 2, 'sms', 'English', 'Malaria can kill your little one. Be sure that  you and your baby sleep under an insecticide treated mosquito net. Be sure that evening time and early dawn your baby is protected from mosquitos by dressing them in something light that covers their legs, feet and arms. Remember to keep your room mosquito free with sprays or by burning coils.  Also clearing bushes around the house, and covering water containers will help control mosquitos. If baby has a fever, is not interested in eating, not sucking well, or spitting up with force, or their eyes or skin look yellow, do not wait to take them to the clinic. Traditional medicines and herbs are not good for babies. Early treatment can save your baby''s life.', 711, 23, 'Malaria', 1, '2014-06-24 01:06:30', '2014-07-06 16:18:35'),
(24, 'fyl-sms-en-24', 2, 'sms', 'English', 'Your baby may have a first tooth by now, but if not they are coming, don?t worry. Teeth come one after another, first the bottom front ones, then the top two middle ones, then the ones along the sides and back. But it can take until the age of 3 years before your baby has all their teeth. Teething can be painful, making your baby a little bit difficult to manage. Some signs that your baby is teething are red, swollen gums, rubbing the ear on the side the tooth is coming, drooling, not sleeping or feeding well, and wanting to bite or suck on anything that comes close to their mouth. Letting your baby suck on your well washed finger can help ease the pain.  Some babies suffer fever or diarrhoea before a tooth comes up, but teething does not cause sickness. If your baby has a fever or diarrhoea, it can be because of so many things so even if you think it is only because of teething, take your baby to clinic to be sure.  ', 931, 24, 'Teething', 1, '2014-06-24 01:06:30', '2014-07-06 16:18:35'),
(25, 'fyl-sms-en-25', 2, 'sms', 'English', 'As your little one is getting their teeth you don''t need to stop breastfeeding.  Babies food needs are mainly met by breastmilk for the first full year of life.  It is not possible in fact for a baby to bite with the first two teeth that come out on the bottom, because their tongue covers the teeth when they are latched on correctly.  But as more teeth come your baby may want to bite down to ease their painful gums.  Your baby doesn''t mean to hurt you.  If your baby bites try to stay calm.  Don''t beat your baby, but stop feeding, look them in the eye and say no! Most babies don''t like being taken from the breast when they are trying to feed, so this usually works well. Then try again to feed.  Most mothers find that their baby stops biting when they do this.  Sometimes your baby may fall asleep at the end of a feeding and bite you without knowing  what they have done, so watch your baby during the feed and remove them from your breast before they fall asleep.  Also, if your baby looks like they are about to bite, put your little finger into the corner of the mouth between the gums so they bite your finger and not your breast. Your baby will soon learn not to bite. Breastmilk is still very important for the protection, growth and development of your baby so keep at it.', 1288, 25, 'Biting nipples', 1, '2014-06-24 01:06:30', '2014-07-06 16:18:35'),
(26, 'fyl-sms-en-26', 2, 'sms', 'English', 'Congratulations! It has not been easy but you and your baby have made it to 6 months. In the 6th month your precious little one should be growing well and should still be putting on weight. Your baby  may even be crawling already. This month your baby needs to attend clinic even if your baby doesn?t have any problems.  Your baby''s weight and length of their body will be measured and charted, and they will be given a dose of Vitamin A to help prevent low blood. The doctor will also make sure all immunizations are up to date, so that your baby is protected from diseases. Make sure you remember to take your baby?s health book. Going to clinic this month gives you the chance to ask any questions you may have about how to make sure your baby stays healthy and can be a good time to discuss family planning if you haven?t already done so."By 6 months your baby is ready for some additional foods along with breastmilk. Your baby is learning and as with all new skills, chewing and swallowing takes practice. Rushing or force feeding leads to chocking or vomiting. Thick foods are also difficult to swallow. Babies this age only eat small mouthfuls, so giving a small amount on the tip of a spoon will help your baby swallow easily.  It is best to feed your baby in a quiet place and take your time.   Koko/porridge should be made rich by adding powdered fish, or beans and a teaspoon of palm oil or groundnut paste.  Also give a small amount of mashed soft fruit like pawpaw or bananas in the day.  When making koko/porridge use clean water and boil food well to kill germs that cause sickness.  Your 6 month old baby will probably not eat more than 1 stew ladle of porridge at a meal, and should be fed two times a day in addition to breastfeeding any other time baby is hungry day and night.  It is important to continue breast feeding for the nutrients, protein,and protection that breast milk provides your baby. ', 1921, 26, 'Vitamin A /Clinic', 1, '2014-06-24 01:06:30', '2014-07-06 16:18:35'),
(27, 'fyl-sms-en-27', 2, 'sms', 'English', 'By 6 months your baby is ready for some additional foods along with breastmilk. Your baby is learning and as with all new skills, chewing and swallowing takes practice. Rushing or force feeding leads to choking or vomiting. Thick foods are also difficult to swallow. Babies this age only eat small mouthfuls, so giving a small amount on the tip of a spoon will help your baby swallow easily.  It is best to feed your baby in a quiet place and take your time.   Pap should be made rich by adding powdered fish, or beans and a teaspoon of palm oil or groundnut paste.  Also give a small amount of mashed soft fruit like pawpaw or bananas in the day.  When making pap use clean water and boil food well to kill germs that cause sickness.  Your 6 month old baby will probably not eat more than 1 stew ladle of food at a meal, and should be fed two times a day in addition to breastfeeding any other time baby is hungry day and night.  It is important to continue breast feeding for the nutrients, protein,and protection that breast milk provides your baby. ', 1053, 27, 'Introducing foods/safety', 1, '2014-06-24 01:06:30', '2014-07-06 16:18:35'),
(28, 'fyl-sms-en-28', 2, 'sms', 'English', 'You know your baby better than anyone so trust yourself if you feel your baby is not well and needs to go to the clinic. Here are a few warning signs that your child is not well: Signs of dehydration, including a dry mouth, lack of tears, sunken fontanelle, (the soft spot on the top of their head) and less than six wet nappies a day.  A fever or if your baby can not or does not want to breastfeed.  Vomiting after eating, or vomiting with great force or a rash that doesn?t fade when the skin is pressed. Sleeping more than usual or too much crying. Trouble  breathing. A swollen belly. Blood or bile (a green substance) in the vomit. Make sure you have immunized baby to help protect them from sickness, and that you are still giving breastmilk to keep your baby healthy, For a fever or signs of dehydration start ORS straight away at home and take the child to clinic without delay.  You can get ORS from your clinic or pharmacy or ask at the clinic how to make it at home.', 978, 28, 'When to go to clinic', 1, '2014-06-24 01:06:30', '2014-07-06 16:18:35'),
(29, 'fyl-sms-en-29', 2, 'sms', 'English', 'While every child develops and learns at their own pace, by 6 months your baby should be able to do some of the following;  Turn towards sounds and voices, copy sounds they hear, blow bubbles from their mouth, roll from back to front or front to back, and might even say mama or baba.  If your baby is not doing any of these things as yet it may mean that there is a problem.  If you have not been to your baby?s 6 month clinic appointment take them this week, so the doctor can make sure that your baby is developing properly and any problems can be addressed early.  This will ensure that your baby has the best chance of growing up well.', 640, 29, 'Milestones', 1, '2014-06-24 01:06:30', '2014-07-06 16:18:35'),
(30, 'fyl-sms-en-30', 2, 'sms', 'English', 'As your baby grows, so do their food needs. At 7 months your baby will now need 3 meals a day as well as breast feeding.  Breastfeeding still gives your baby protection from certain sickness and provides nutrition that keeps your baby growing strong and healthy.   Babies need protein, (such as meat, fish, eggs, or beans), vegetables (such as Ewedu or okro) and fruit.    Your baby will eat much of the same foods as they did at 6 months but you may add more kinds of foods, mashed chicken or fish, well cooked eggs, mashed liver, and fruits like mango, orange, pawpaw, pineapple and avocado pear are all good. The food can be mashed a bit less than last month.  Giving soft foods that are easy to pick up, like sliced banana are good for your baby to practice self feeding. There are a few things you should avoid giving your baby. Your baby can choke on whole groundnuts, and honey has germs that can make your baby sick. Tea and coffee contain things that prevent your baby?s body from being able to make use of iron that is in his food which causes low blood in your baby. ', 1078, 30, 'Food types', 1, '2014-06-24 01:06:30', '2014-07-06 16:18:35'),
(31, 'fyl-sms-en-31', 2, 'sms', 'English', 'Now that your baby is moving around more, it may be more difficult to keep them covered up, but you still need to protect them from mosquito bites in the evening and early dawn.  Light clothes that cover their feet, legs and arms will protect them when they are awake and making sure they sleep under an insecticide treated mosquito net during naps and at night will also help keep them safe from malaria.  Remember that malaria is not the only sickness that causes a fever, weakness, diahorrea and vomiting.  If your child has any of these problems, start ORS at home and go to the clinic straight away to get proper medical attention.  It can mean the difference between life and death for your baby.', 702, 31, 'Malaria', 1, '2014-06-24 01:06:30', '2014-07-06 16:18:35'),
(32, 'fyl-sms-en-32', 2, 'sms', 'English', ' By now you have settled into taking good care of your little one, but are you taking care of yourself? It is best to continue breastfeeding until baby is two years of age, but if you are not eating well this will be difficult for you. You may be feeling too tired or fall sick easy.  While breastfeeding you need to be sure that you are eating protein (like meat, chicken, beans, or eggs), vegetables (tomatos, greens, okro), and some fruit.  Continuing to breastfeed in the night and between your baby?s small meals keeps them healthy and growing strong. Be aware that you can get pregnant even if your period has not started back and if you have seen your period, you definitely can get pregnant.  Be sure you have been to the family planning clinic and have chosen one of the many methods available like the pill, IUD, condoms, or injections to be sure that you don?t get pregnant again too soon. If for any reason you do find yourself pregnant again too soon, speak with your midwife regarding your options. Getting the proper medical advice is far safer than using herbs or other traditional medicines which can cause problems now or with future pregnancies.', 1164, 32, 'Mamas Health', 1, '2014-06-24 01:06:30', '2014-07-06 16:18:35'),
(33, 'fyl-sms-en-33', 2, 'sms', 'English', 'As you baby is now eating solid foods it is easier for them to get cases of diahorrea.  To start treating diahorrea at home you can use Zinc and Oral Rehydration Salts.  For your baby older than 6 months dissolve 20mg tablet in a small amount of clean boiled water or breast milk and give to your baby.  Give once a day for 14 days even if the diarrhea stops earlier.  For ORS put one sachet of ORS in a clean bowl and add one beer bottle or two mineral bottles full of clean boiled water and mix well.  Give this to the child while you prepare to go to the clinic.  You may also give clean boiled water, rice water, or garri water in addition to the ORS. If your baby is vomiting everything, refuses to drink or eat, is weak or limp or has blood in the stool you must rush to the clinic immediately for further medical attention. Your baby can die from dehydration caused by diahorrea.', 886, 33, 'ORS/Zinc', 1, '2014-06-24 01:06:30', '2014-07-06 16:18:35'),
(34, 'fyl-sms-en-34', 2, 'sms', 'English', 'If you haven?t started already you may now feel ready to start having sexual relations with your husband again. If you haven?t started a family planning method yet, you should use a condom. Remember that condoms not only protect you from getting pregnant, but protect you from HIV and other sexually transmitted infections. Remember that you may get pregnant again even if you are not ready. If you do find yourself pregnant again too soon, seek advice from your midwife or doctor at the clinic. If for any reason your pregnancy is terminated outside of a medical clinic make sure you go to your midwife or doctor to see that all is well.  ', 640, 34, 'Family Planning', 1, '2014-06-24 01:06:30', '2014-07-06 16:18:35'),
(35, 'fyl-sms-en-35', 2, 'sms', 'English', 'A healthy 8 month old needs to eat meals 3 times a day, as well as breastfeeding day and night . Your baby should eat one soup ladle of food (mashed yam, agidi, mashed plantain, ogi) and one stew ladle of stew that has mashed fish, meat, chicken or beans in it.  At each meal your baby should also take  2 tablespoons of mashed fruit or vegetable.  It is best that the main caregiver feeds baby, but if your baby eats best when a particular person feeds them you should allow. If your baby refuses to eat it may not mean that they are not hungry, but maybe they do not like the taste of the food. Be patient and keep trying to offer your baby the food. If they still refuse try changing the food by adding different things to change the taste or change the thickness.  Forcing or rushing feeding can easily cause your baby to choke, or learn that eating is not pleasant.   If your baby is not well, breastfeed plenty and feed smaller meals more times in a day to help them get better quickly. When your baby is better add one extra meal a day for 2 weeks so they can regain strength lost from being sick. ', 1105, 35, 'Food types', 1, '2014-06-24 01:06:30', '2014-07-06 16:18:35'),
(36, 'fyl-sms-en-36', 2, 'sms', 'English', 'By now, you may have already told your baby that the telephone is not a toy, not to throw things, or not to pull your hair. At this age your baby may start to test your authority by not following your simple instructions. They are not being naughty or willful ? just curious. They can not remember things you tell them for more than a few seconds at a time. Babies at this age are learning from everything they see and touch and like to pick up and touch everything. It is not good to beat your baby, the best  is to say "no" and then give them something else to play with that is safe.  Keep sharp objects like knives, cutlass, nails, used razor blades tin cans, pieces of glass and mirror away from the play areas. Babies must not ever be put down to play in cooking areas or near lanterns or candles, as burns are a main cause of accidents for little ones. Keep your baby safe by making sure that someone is carefully watching at all times.', 943, 36, 'Milestones', 1, '2014-06-24 01:06:30', '2014-07-06 16:18:35'),
(37, 'fyl-sms-en-37', 2, 'sms', 'English', 'Your husband or family could be telling you that you should have another child or that taking family planning is not good.  Getting pregnant again now can cause you to bleed too much at your next delivery, which can cause you to loose your womb or even cause your death. There are many options when it comes to family planning, like pills, injections (Depo Provera) or an intra-uterine device (implant). Women can have different reactions to family planning methods but there will be a choice for you that works well.  Attend the clinic to get family planning counseling and choose a method that will work for you.', 614, 37, 'Family Planning', 1, '2014-06-24 01:06:30', '2014-07-06 16:18:35'),
(38, 'fyl-sms-en-38', 2, 'sms', 'English', 'Coughs and colds are common in children and usually end without needing medication, But in babies coughs can be serious. Left untreated colds or coughs can turn into pneumonia which can be deadly for your baby. Watch and listen to your baby as they breathe.  If the lower part of the chest sucks in when the child takes a breath or if the belly is moving in and out when they breathe, or your baby sounds like they are snoring but are not asleep your baby is in trouble and needs to see the doctor straight.  You can help prevent pneumonia by protecting your baby from breathing in smoke.  The smoke from tobacco, cooking fires, burning rubbish, and fires to clear land are all dangerous for your little ones growing lungs. If the doctor gives baby medicine to take make sure you understand the directions very well and follow them carefully.  Complete the whole course of medicine.  Be sure to continue breastfeeding. Breastmilk helps your baby get better quick and is the only food they require.  ', 999, 38, 'Coughs/ colds', 1, '2014-06-24 01:06:30', '2014-07-06 16:18:35'),
(39, 'fyl-sms-en-39', 2, 'sms', 'English', 'Now is the week to immunize your baby against measles and yellow fever.  Measles is one of the 9 childhood killers and is extremely dangerous for children that are not eating well.  Measles spread very fast and causes severe diarrhea.   Signs of measles are fever and a rash that have lasted more than 3 days along with a cough, runny nose or red eyes. Measles can cause death. Yellow fever also puts a baby''s life at risk. It is spread by mosquitos and signs of yellow fever are the same as malaria, which are, fever, red eyes, vomiting and not wanting to eat. If any of your children have these symptoms take them straight to the health centre. Immunizations are free at government health centres and only work if given before the disease strikes so it is important to immunize on time.   If your baby gets a small rash from the injection, or a slight fever continue to breastfeed often to help them feel better quick.  Breastfeeding protects baby from sickness and disease, but immunizations protect baby from childhood killers. Make sure that all your baby?s immunizations are to date.', 1089, 39, 'Measles/yellow fever', 1, '2014-06-24 01:08:18', '2014-07-06 16:18:35'),
(40, 'fyl-sms-en-40', 2, 'sms', 'English', 'Keeping your house environment clean and washing your hands keeps the whole family safe from diarrhea and other sickness.  When changing nappies, all faeces should be disposed of in a latrine or toilet, or buried. If you have washed faeces off nappies in a bucket of water, the water should be thrown far away from the house, cooking areas, and away from where other children play. Always wash your hands with soap and water before feeding your child, after changing babies nappies, after toileting, before handling any food, cooking or eating. Babies now also like to put their own hands and anything they can grab into their mouth, so clean their hands often and watch that your baby doesn''t pick rubbish or anything else from the ground to put in their mouth. Don?t be afraid to share what you have learned about handwashing with others in your household. A clean house and clean hands will protect your new precious gift, and the whole family from sickness.  ', 963, 40, 'Handwashing for family', 1, '2014-06-24 01:08:18', '2014-07-06 16:18:35'),
(41, 'fyl-sms-en-41', 2, 'sms', 'English', 'By now your baby probably has some teeth and likes chewing.  They also like to start using their fingers to feed themselves small pieces of food. Snack or (something small between meals) is a good time to let your baby practice feeding themselves.  Your baby still needs to be fed three times a day and now you need to add one snack. This gives the extra energy needed to grow strong.    Now each meal should contain the following: 1 soup ladle of staple (rice, yam, ogi, sweet potato) and one stew ladle of stew/thick soup that has a bit of mashed fish, meat or beans, egg or agushi.  Another option is 2 soup ladles of thick Pap which has 1 teaspoon of palm oil/groundnut paste and fish or bean powder added to be sure your baby gets enough protien. Each meal should have 2 tablespoons of mashed fruit or vegetables. Take time when picking a snack for your baby so that it is not sweet.  Toffees and sweet biscuits are not good snacks.  A banana, pawpaw, poofpof or roasted plantain is a good snack. It?s important to continue breastfeeding between meals but breastfeeding is no longer a substitute for a meal or snack. ', 1122, 41, 'Food types/self feeding', 1, '2014-06-24 01:08:18', '2014-07-06 16:18:35'),
(42, 'fyl-sms-en-42', 2, 'sms', 'English', 'Your baby is growing and may even say 1 or 2 words, but may also still cry a lot.  This doesn?t mean that your baby is bad, it is just that they really have no other way to tell you what they need. By now you probably recognize different types of crying depending on what your baby is trying to tell you. It may be that they are saying they have a wet nappy, are hungry, are tired, or just need some attention. Some people may tell you that you are spoiling your child by playing with them & attending to their crying, but babies at this age cannot be spoiled. Spoiled children have learned to use negative behaviour to get what they want. Your baby is too young to do this. You may find if you give attention to them when they cry, they will actually cry less. Setting limits is necessary but giving baby love & attention will build a trust bond that lasts forever', 865, 42, 'Crying babies', 1, '2014-06-24 01:08:18', '2014-07-06 16:18:35'),
(43, 'fyl-sms-en-43', 2, 'sms', 'English', 'Now that your baby is eating prepared foods and they unfortunately have more chance of getting diarrhoea.  If your child has three or more watery stools in a row your child has diarrhea and should go to the clinic. You can start ORS at home using one sachet from the pharmacy. Mix the sachet with one big beer bottle, or two mineral bottles of clean boiled water.  Along with the ORS you may dissolve a zinc  tablet  in a little bit of clean water and give once a day for 14 days. Use 10mg Zinc tablet for children under 6 months and 20mg for children over 6 months. You can also give clean boiled water, rice water, pap, or coconut water in addition to starting ORS and Zinc. If your child is vomiting everything, is very weak or you notice blood in the stool your child is in serious danger and must go to the clinic straight away. ', 834, 43, 'ORS/Zinc', 1, '2014-06-24 01:08:18', '2014-07-06 16:18:35'),
(44, 'fyl-sms-en-44', 2, 'sms', 'English', 'Malaria can kill your little one. Be sure that  you and your baby sleep under an insecticide treated mosquito net. Be sure that evening time and early dawn your baby is protected from mosquitos by dressing them in something light that covers their legs, feet and arms. Remember to keep your room mosquito free with sprays or by burning coils.  Also clearing bushes around the house, and covering water containers will help control mosquitos. If baby has a fever, is not interested in eating, or spitting up with force, or their eyes or skin look yellow, do not wait to take them to the clinic. Traditional medicines and herbs are not good for babies and not all malaria medicines from the pharmacy are right for babies. Early treatment can save your baby''s life.', 762, 44, 'Malaria', 1, '2014-06-24 01:08:18', '2014-07-06 16:18:35'),
(45, 'fyl-sms-en-45', 2, 'sms', 'English', 'Now your baby likes to pick small pieces of food to feed themselves.  While you should allow them to feed themselves, some things like whole groundnuts,  are just the right size to get stuck in their throat choking them, Also, remember that your baby is using their hands to put things in their mouths so it?s good that you are sure their hands are clean before they go into their mouth. Wash them well with soap and water and wash your hands with soap  and water before preparing food or feeding your baby. This will prevent diarrhoea and worms which are dangerous for all young children. When feeding your baby make sure that spoons, bowls and cups are well washed before using them. Other ways to protect your baby from diarrhoea are to heat food very well before serving, and give your baby fresh food.  Foods that are stored should be covered and in a cool place, but food that has been stored for more than 2 days will make your baby sick.  ', 947, 45, 'Food & hygiene', 1, '2014-06-24 01:08:18', '2014-07-06 16:18:35');
INSERT INTO `messages` (`id`, `message_key`, `content_id`, `content_type`, `language`, `content`, `length`, `order`, `tags`, `modified_by`, `created_at`, `updated_at`) VALUES
(46, 'fyl-sms-en-46', 2, 'sms', 'English', 'For your child to be healthy and continue to grow and develop well your baby needs a variety of foods.  Energy foods are like wood for a fire.  They give your child energy to grow. Small amounts of staple foods like ogi, plaintain , pap or eba will give your child energy. Protein foods help your baby develop. Add protein to your child?s meal by adding beans, Ewa, soyabeans, egg, milk, fish, prawns, agushi or meat. Adding 1 teaspoon of palm oil gives your baby Vitamin A to help their eyesight and fight infections. Vitamins and minerals are needed for strong bones and to prevent low blood. Greens like efo, collard greens, ewedu, are all good sources of vitamins and minerals.  Lastly, growing babies need vitamin C from fruits.  Mango, pineapple and banana are good fruits for your child. Giving a variety of foods keeps your child interested in eating and keeps them healthy.', 882, 46, 'feeding', 1, '2014-06-24 01:08:18', '2014-07-06 16:18:35'),
(47, 'fyl-sms-en-47', 2, 'sms', 'English', 'As your baby starts to take different kinds of foods, the stools will become thicker, darker and a lot more smelly. Your baby can also suffer constipation.  You may see them pushing hard as they try to pass stools, or they don?t make any faeces for more than 2 days and the faeces look like small, dry pellets. Constipation causes pain, a tight belly, and your baby may cry easily as they are uncomfortable.  Sometimes you may see blood streaked stools which could be due to anal fissures (tiny cracks in the skin) caused by passing hard stools. Your baby is dehydrated if they are weak, limp, have sunken eyes or a sunken fontanelle. Continue breastfeeding between meals as breastmilk helps to prevent the germs which cause diarrhoea, keeps your child hydrated and the stools soft preventing constipation. If your child becomes dehydrated, start ORS and Zinc at home and go to the clinic without delay. ', 904, 47, 'Constipation/ diarrhoea/ Breastfeeding', 1, '2014-06-24 01:08:18', '2014-07-06 16:18:35'),
(48, 'fyl-sms-en-48', 2, 'sms', 'English', ' Your baby will soon be celebrating their one year birthday.  This is great.  By now your baby should be able to do some of the following things: Say ''dada'' and ''mama'' to the right parent.  Play a clapping game. Stand alone for a couple of seconds, copy others activities, put things into a container, understand simple instructions, drink from a cup, say one word other than mama and dada, or stoop from a standing position. Some children will have delays in a particular area, such as walking, while the rest of their skills continue developing on or ahead of schedule. If that''s the case for your child, it may just mean they are concentrating so hard on talking or understanding that the brain has forgot about walking for a small time. Also, perhaps your child is walking already but does not say anything yet.  As they are learning new things all the time,  they should be encouraged, and praised when they have learned something new or said something new. It will give the child the confidence to keep learning and trying. For all children, boys or girls, playing with them, singing to them, telling them stories, and talking to them helps them learn to think. Don?t be afraid to take your baby to the clinic if  you think something is wrong or you are worried about how your baby is growing.  ', 1301, 48, 'Milestones', 1, '2014-06-24 01:08:18', '2014-07-06 16:18:35'),
(49, 'fyl-sms-en-49', 2, 'sms', 'English', 'At eleven months your baby is starting to eat more food at each feeding. They should still eat 3 times a day and a small snack, between meals.  Breastfeeding when baby wants including in the night time is still important for the extra energy and nutrients.  Your baby can eat many different kinds of food and actually eat better when different foods are offered in the day. Also, your baby should be eating some snacks by themselves, like small pieces of soft fruit.   Sweets, toffees sweet bisquits and minerals are not good for babies. They contain too much sugar, and minerals can give diahorrea. Don?t force your child to eat, and if baby has been ill give foods and breastmilk more often than usual in order to help your baby recover quickly.  If your baby has not been eating, is losing weight, limp or lethargic, hair color is changing, make sure that you take them to the clinic. If you are told that your baby has low blood the doctor can help and may give vitamins to supplement the food you are giving. ', 1014, 49, 'Food types', 1, '2014-06-24 01:08:18', '2014-07-06 16:18:35'),
(50, 'fyl-sms-en-50', 2, 'sms', 'English', 'You may have already started disciplining your child, but here are a few tips about discipline,. First, we need to know that discipline means teaching, not punishing.  Babies play because it is fun, and play is also how they learn and grow. They are not able to understand things like their older brothers or sisters.  Babies don''t yet know right from wrong so they are not trying to be naughty or bad, even if, they seem troublesome . They learn by doing things, and then watching to see what happens and how you or others will react to their behaviour. Like what happens when they turn over their cup of water. Also, babies can not remember things for long so if you told baby not to touch something one day, they may not remember not to touch it the next day. Lastly, all babies learn by copying what they see people do, therefore we need to set  good examples for them to follow. Be patient and try to give baby something else to do when they are doing something you don''t like. ', 983, 50, 'Discipline', 1, '2014-06-24 01:08:18', '2014-07-06 16:18:35'),
(51, 'fyl-sms-en-51', 2, 'sms', 'English', 'At one year your baby needs to go to the clinic, even if they are healthy. The time at the clinic gives you a chance to make sure everything is well with your baby.  It is a good time to ask any questions that you may have, and a time to make sure that all your baby?s immunizations are complete.  Completing all immunizations before one year will make sure that your child is protected from the childhood killers. Make sure you remember to take your baby?s health card with you.  At this clinic visit your baby will be weighed and measured and given another dose of Vitamin A.  If needed, the doctor will give some vitamins to help keep baby growing strong.  Each of your children has a better start at life, if there is more time between your pregnancies, so if you haven?t started a Family planning method yet, use this trip to the clinic to get started. Family planning is good for you and for your family.', 910, 51, 'Clinic', 1, '2014-06-24 01:08:18', '2014-07-06 16:18:35'),
(52, 'fyl-sms-en-52', 2, 'sms', 'English', 'Congratulations! Your baby is now 1 year old.  You have done a great job. Ensuring your baby eats well, gets timely care when they are not well and receives all of their immunizations on schedule is one of the best things you can do for all of your children, so that they grow up strong and healthy .  We hope that the messages have been helpful and that you will be able to share some of what you learned about taking good care of your baby with your friends and family. We also hope that you will be able use the information you have received to ensure that all of the children in your family stay healthy.   ', 611, 52, 'Congratulations', 1, '2014-06-24 01:08:18', '2014-07-06 16:18:35'),
(53, 'fyl-voice-en-1', 2, 'voice', 'English', 'The first PNC visits are very important.  If for any reason you gave birth outside of a medical facility, you need to attend PNC within 24 hours of giving birth. Even if you feel fine and your baby seems well it is important to go. Because of the amount of blood lost during delivery you can become anemic or have very low blood. You will be given a dose of Vitamin A, and another one when you go to the PNC visit 2 days after the birth which will help raise your blood levels.  Your baby will be weighed, measured and get their first immunizations which are very important to protect your baby against Polio and TB.  You can also register your baby for a birth certificate at this time. It is best to go to PNC two times during the first week of your baby?s life and again when your baby is 6 weeks old. If you haven?t been yet be sure to go this week. Chord care: When your baby is born, the  umbilical chord is cut freeing you from your baby. Once the chord is cut there is a wound where the chord was cut that looks like a tree stump. Keep this wound dry and clean. Don''t put anything on it like  soap, traditional herbs, shea butter or even surgical spirit. Make sure that baby napkins don''t rub or cover the wound. Don''t force the stump of the chord to fall off as it will fall by itself in 10-12 days. Infections of the stump can cause death. See a doctor straight away if there is bleeding from the chord, or if you see any redness or pus around it.', 1457, 1, '1st PNC', 1, '2014-06-24 00:50:22', '2014-07-06 16:18:35'),
(54, 'fyl-voice-en-2', 2, 'voice', 'English', 'By now your baby?s umbilical cord stump should be dry and may have fallen already. If you see any puss or redness at the area take your baby to clinic right away as infections can be dangerous to your new baby. Also, every baby has a soft spot on the top of his or her head where the bones have not yet sealed giving your baby''s brain room to grow. It will start to close by itself at about 6 months.This soft spot is not an ulcer and you should not put hot compresses or any herbal medicines on it. The spot should be flat or raised a bit when you feel it. If the spot has sunk down and it feels like a hole you must go to the clinic as your baby is not well.  Do not try to shape your baby''s head as this is dangerous and can cause serious damage to your little one''s brain.  ', 778, 2, 'Fontenelle/ Cord Care', 1, '2014-06-24 00:50:22', '2014-07-06 16:18:35'),
(55, 'fyl-voice-en-3', 2, 'voice', 'English', 'Breast-fed babies are healthier, stronger and suffer fewer sicknesses than babies that are fed other foods or drinks. Breast-milk alone 8 - 12 times a day, is all baby needs to eat for the first 6 months of life.  Breast milk contains water so your baby doesn?t need to be given water. The right positioning during feeding is important for your baby to eat well.  Your baby''s whole body should be turned to face you, and you and your baby should be belly to belly. Signs that your baby is feeding well are: baby''s chin is touching your breast, more of the dark skin around your nipple can be seen above your baby''s mouth than below it, your baby takes long, deep sucks, and you don''t feel any pain in the nipple. Both of your breasts should feel empty when your baby is finished. If you are worried that your baby is not getting enough to eat, don''t be afraid to ask your midwife. They can help you so that you are sure that your little one gets all they need to grow healthy and strong. ', 988, 3, 'EBF', 1, '2014-06-24 00:50:22', '2014-07-06 16:18:35'),
(56, 'fyl-voice-en-4', 2, 'voice', 'English', 'Malaria is very dangerous to a newborn baby and is caused by the bite of mosquitos. Be sure that  you and your baby sleep under an insecticide treated mosquito net. Be sure that evening time and early dawn your baby is protected from mosquitos by dressing them in something light that covers their legs, feet and arms. Remember to keep your room mosquito free with sprays or by burning coils.  Also clearing bushes around the house, and covering water containers will help control mosquitos. If baby has a fever, is not interested in eating, not sucking well, or spitting up with force, or their eyes or skin look yellow, do not wait to take them to the clinic. Early treatment can save your baby''s life.', 704, 4, 'Malaria', 1, '2014-06-24 00:50:22', '2014-07-06 16:18:35'),
(57, 'fyl-voice-en-5', 2, 'voice', 'English', 'Good hand washing practices can prevent the spread of diseases such as polio, rotovirus, typhoid and cholera and eye infections.  It is always important to keep your home environment clean, but the best way to keep germs from causing a problem for your baby is by washing your hands. Wash your hands with soap and clean water, rubbing them well to remove the germs.  Always wash your hands before handling your newborn, and after changing your baby''s nappies.  And of course, wash hands after toileting, after handling raw food and always before cooking or eating. Don''t be afraid to ask others to wash their hands before holding or touching  your new baby as well. We can''t protect babies from everything that might make them sick but hand washing is an important step to help keep your baby and the rest of your family healthy.', 829, 5, 'Infection Control/ hygiene', 1, '2014-06-24 01:05:34', '2014-07-06 16:18:35'),
(58, 'fyl-voice-en-6', 2, 'voice', 'English', 'Immunization gives the body protection from certain diseases.  An immunization tells the body to create antibodies which are like soldiers that fight off the disease. This week your baby needs to receive immunization against Tetanus/diphtheria/whooping cough (DPT), influenzaB(HiB), Hepatitis B, Polio, Rotavirus and Pneumonia, which are all dangerous diseases that can kill.  Immunizations are free at government facilities. Remember to always take your baby?s health card so the jabs can be recorded.  Immunizations are not harmful and can protect your baby from deadly diseases.  ', 583, 6, 'Immunization', 1, '2014-06-24 01:05:34', '2014-07-06 16:18:35'),
(59, 'fyl-voice-en-7', 2, 'voice', 'English', 'MEN: Your wife needs to report to PNC around now to make sure she is fine, after giving birth. One thing that should be talked about at PNC is contraception in order to space your children at least 2 years apart. Contraception methods are a personal choice for every couple and it gives your wife?s body enough time to fully recover before getting pregnant again. Using contraception is not so that your wife can be promiscuous or go outside of your marriage. Getting pregnant again too soon can put her life at risk, as her blood levels may still be low. She can also bleed  too much with the next delivery. While breastfeeding she may be protected from getting pregnant for some months,  but she can still get pregnant even if breastfeeding. Speak to your doctor about a contraception method that will work for you and your wife, take time to decide and start the method as soon as your wife is no longer exclusively breast feeding.', 934, 7, 'MEN: Contraception/Postnatal clinic', 1, '2014-06-24 01:05:34', '2014-07-06 16:18:35'),
(60, 'fyl-voice-en-8', 2, 'voice', 'English', 'Babies only know how to breath through their nose, so if the nose is stopped up your baby can''t breath.  A baby should not take more than 50 breaths in one minute. Watch your baby as they breathe.  If the lower part of the chest sinks in when the child takes a breath or if the belly is moving in and out when they breathe your baby is in trouble and needs to go to the clinic straight.  You can help prevent pneumonia by protecting your baby from sleeping directly under a fan, and from breathing in smoke. The smoke from tobacco, cooking fires, burning rubbish, and fires to clear land are all dangerous for your little ones growing lungs. If the doctor gives baby medicine to take make sure you understand the directions very well and follow them carefully.  Complete the whole course of medicine.  Be sure to continue breastfeeding. Breastmilk helps your baby get better quick and is the only food they require.  ', 917, 8, 'Pneumonia', 1, '2014-06-24 01:05:35', '2014-07-06 16:18:35'),
(61, 'fyl-voice-en-9', 2, 'voice', 'English', 'Your baby is growing very fast now and should put on almost 1kg a month. Your baby should also be getting stronger now, but you still need to support the head when carrying or when your baby is tied to your back.  If your baby is not getting stronger, not sucking well at the breast, is coughing with force, vomiting, or has difficulty breathing you must report to the clinic straight. It is a sign that your baby is not well. If your baby seems weak, eyes are sunken or the fontanelle feels like a hole, your baby needs proper medical attention. Keep up with breastfeeding and remember you don?t need to give any other food or liquid, even if  baby seems hungry.  The more you breastfeed the more milk your body will make so your baby will always get enough.  ', 761, 9, 'milestones/ danger signs', 1, '2014-06-24 01:05:35', '2014-07-06 16:18:35'),
(62, 'fyl-voice-en-10', 2, 'voice', 'English', 'This week your baby needs another immunization injection to protect them from the childhood killer diseases. Immunizations are free at government facilities and going to the clinic gives you a chance to ask any questions you may have about how your baby is doing.  If you are having any problems breastfeeding now is the time to speak to the doctor. Your baby should still be drinking only breastmilk as it gives baby everything they need to grow strong and healthy.  Even if it is hot outside, your baby doesn''t need water, as breastmilk contains water.  Do not start giving solid foods. Your baby''s belly is not ready to digest solid foods and feeding solids before 6 months of age, causes serious belly problems and diarrhoea. Breastmilk alone is the best and only food your baby should eat until 6 months of age.', 816, 10, 'Immunization/EBF', 1, '2014-06-24 01:05:35', '2014-07-06 16:18:35'),
(63, 'fyl-voice-en-11', 2, 'voice', 'English', 'IF your are exclusively breast feeding which means feeding every four hours or more often through the day as well as night time feeds, and your period has not returned, you are protected from getting pregnant at this time, but it is not too early to start thinking about using contraceptives.  If you are not exclusively breast feeding on demand, you''ll begin to ovulate before you have a period and you risk getting pregnant again too soon.  Discuss birth spacing and contraceptives with your husband and speak to your midwife to find a method that will work for both of you. Remember that breast feeding is all your baby needs to stay healthy and grow well for the first 6 months of life, so continue breastfeeding exclusively to protect yourself from getting pregnant as well as giving your baby the best chance at staying healthy. ', 835, 11, 'Contraception/EBF/LAM', 1, '2014-06-24 01:05:35', '2014-07-06 16:18:35'),
(64, 'fyl-voice-en-12', 2, 'voice', 'English', 'In hot weather babies can overheat easily which is dangerous.  If you aren''t sure whether your child is overheated, touch the skin. Damp hot skin is a sign that they are too warm.  Keep your child cooler by dressing them in loose, light, cotton clothing, and use a cotton hat instead of a wooly one.   To keep your child cooler at night, make sure your mattress is firm and your baby only has a light covering. If you are warm so is your baby. You can cool down a hot or feverish baby by wiping his bare body with a face cloth soaked in cool water. Cooling your baby makes sure they don?t become dehydrated or suffer heat stroke or heat exhaustion. Breastfeeding day and night also keeps baby hydrated and cooler."When your baby is sleeping in the bed with you, make sure your mattress is firm: Your baby could suffocate or overheat if sleeping on a soft mattress. If your bed has a frame, a headboard or is against a wall, make sure the mattress fits tight with the edges of the bed so that there is no risk of your baby falling into the gap. This risk is biggest for for three to 10-month-olds. Your baby only needs a light covering at night.  If you are feeling warm enough then so is your baby. Finally to protect against malaria your baby must sleep under an insecticide treated mosquito net. Most 10-week-old babies still wake up in the middle of the night to eat. When baby wakes up in the night you still need to give them breastmilk as it is important to help them grow.', 1479, 12, 'heat/clothing', 1, '2014-06-24 01:05:35', '2014-07-06 16:18:35'),
(65, 'fyl-voice-en-13', 2, 'voice', 'English', 'Your baby is probably showing signs that they want to eat real food. They are learning to copy you as you eat, as well as learning to reach out and pick things.  Just because they can reach and pick up the food does not mean that the belly is ready to manage the food.  Resist the feeling that your baby needs to eat solid food.  If your baby is gaining weight, looks healthy and seems happy after breastfeeds, then you can feel sure they are getting what they need. If your baby is making 6-8 wet nappies in a day and faeces is soft and yellowish then your baby is eating enough. If your baby takes to the breast quickly and eats well without slipping off, crying or falling asleep then they are eating well. If your baby is taking a good mouthful of the breast, sucking and swallowing without causing you pain then your baby is doing well.  If you have any questions don''t be afraid to ask a doctor or nurse for help. Remember that breastmilk  is all your baby needs until six months of age. Giving any other foods or water can cause diarrhoea and serious belly problems for your baby.', 1087, 13, 'EBF', 1, '2014-06-24 01:05:35', '2014-07-06 16:18:35'),
(66, 'fyl-voice-en-14', 2, 'voice', 'English', 'MEN: This week your baby needs another immunization to protect them from the childhood killer diseases. Immunizations are free at the government facilities. Even though it may seem like a long wait to see the nurse or doctor, it is a small price to pay in order to keep your baby healthy. Your baby should still be drinking only breastmilk as it gives them everything they need to grow strong and healthy. Your wife will continue to make enough breastmilk as long as she continues to breastfeed regularly and is eating well.  After the injection your baby may cry a lot or show a small rash. Be sure your wife breastfeeds frequently to help your baby recover from the injection.  If  your baby is very warm (fever), vomiting with force, not breathing well or coughing with force it is a sign that baby is sick. Go to the clinic before it is too late.', 850, 14, 'Immunization /EBF/danger signs', 1, '2014-06-24 01:05:35', '2014-07-06 16:18:35'),
(67, 'fyl-voice-en-15', 2, 'voice', 'English', 'Diarrhoea kills babies by draining liquid from the body thus dehydrating the child. A child?s life is in danger if there are three or more watery stools in a day or if there is blood in the faeces.  Do not give your baby water, minerals, traditional medicines or herbs. These can make the sickness worse. Starting ORS at home while you are organizing to get your baby to the clinic can help save your baby?s life.  Get the ORS sachet at a pharmacy or chemical seller.  Pour one sachet into a clean bowl. Add 1 big beer bottle or 2 mineral bottles of clean water, mix well and give to your baby. Also, breastfeed often to help replace fluid lost in stools. Even if you have started treating your baby at home you still need to take your child to the clinic as soon as possible, so that the problem that caused the diarrhoea can be addressed. ', 841, 15, 'Diarrhoea/ EBF', 1, '2014-06-24 01:05:35', '2014-07-06 16:18:35'),
(68, 'fyl-voice-en-16', 2, 'voice', 'English', 'As your baby reaches 3 months old, you may feel tired from breast feeding, or think it takes too much time and energy to continue giving only breast milk. You may also worry that your baby will not take foods at 6 months because they will only like the breast.  Your baby will be healthier and stronger if you make the sacrifice of time and energy now for your child.  Taking care of a sick baby takes more time, energy and costs more money than if you continue with only breast milk. If you are busy working, you can express milk from the breast and it can be given to your baby from a clean cup. After 6 months you can slowly introduce soft foods that your child will enjoy because their body will be ready to cope with foods in additional to breast milk. Doing the best for your child now ensures they grow up well.', 818, 16, 'EBF', 1, '2014-06-24 01:05:35', '2014-07-06 16:18:35'),
(69, 'fyl-voice-en-17', 2, 'voice', 'English', 'Keeping your house environment clean and washing your hands keeps the whole family safe from diarrhoea and other sickness.  When changing nappies, all faeces should be disposed of in a latrine or toilet, or buried. If you have washed faeces off nappies in a bucket of water, the water should be thrown far away from the house, cooking areas, and away from where other children play. Always wash your hands with soap and water before feeding your child, after changing babies nappies, after toileting, before handling any food, cooking or eating. Babies now also like to put their own hands and anything they can grab into their mouth, so clean their hands often and watch that your baby doesn''t pick rubbish or anything else from the ground to put in their mouth. Don?t be afraid to share what you have learned about handwashing with others in your household. A clean house and clean hands will protect your new precious gift, and the whole family from sickness.  ', 964, 17, 'Handwashing for family', 1, '2014-06-24 01:06:30', '2014-07-06 16:18:35'),
(70, 'fyl-voice-en-18', 2, 'voice', 'English', ' Malaria is very dangerous for small babies and if not treated right away can cause death. Babies can not tell us when a mosquito is troubling them or they are being bit, so we must do everything possible to protect them from mosquito bites.  First, your baby must sleep under an insecticide treated mosquito net. Also, make sure that the room your baby sleeps in does not have hanging clothes.  Fold the clothes away so mosquitos have no place to hide. If you spray the room make sure that you spray at least 30 minutes before baby goes in the room, as the spray is not good for their lungs.  In the evening and early morning hours make sure that your baby is well covered  including feet and legs with light colored clothing to protect them.  Lastly, if your baby has a fever, is limp or weak, does not want to eat or vomits, has a fever or doesn''t seem well, take them to clinic straight away. If baby has fever, you must cool baby down by wiping them with a face cloth soaked in cool water while you are preparing to go to the clinic.  Malaria does not go away by itself and traditional medicines are not good for babies.  Understand how to give any medicines the doctor gives and give the full course. And as always, breastfeeding helps baby get better quick so be sure to feed and feed often.', 1298, 18, 'Malaria reminder', 1, '2014-06-24 01:06:30', '2014-07-06 16:18:35'),
(71, 'fyl-voice-en-19', 2, 'voice', 'English', 'MEN:  Even though your wife is still breastfeeding, she can now become pregnant again. It is time to discuss family planning and spacing of your children. Family planning methods affect each woman differently, but none of the methods make women go outside of their marriage. There are many choices when it comes to contraception or family planning, some which are short term and others that protect for a longer time.  Spacing children allows your wife?s body to fully recover before getting pregnant again, ensuring that she doesn?t bleed too much with the next pregnancy, and allows the family time to financially prepare for another child. Children are a gift from God, and planning when to have your next one makes sure that each child has the best chance at life. You can get more information by attending family planning counseling at the clinic with your wife, which will help you both make the best decision for your family. It?s time to start a method now. ', 966, 19, 'MEN: Family Planning', 1, '2014-06-24 01:06:30', '2014-07-06 16:18:35'),
(72, 'fyl-voice-en-20', 2, 'voice', 'English', 'Most cases of diahorrea sicknesses in babies comes giving your young baby foods other than breastmilk.  Food and water carry bacterias like typhoid and cholera. While an adult can usually recover from diahorrea your baby?s body is not strong enough to recover from diahorrea and can die.  Even if you feel your baby wants to eat foods other than breastmilk, their body is not ready to cope with bacteria?s that come along with foods.  Do not give Pap, Ewedu, fish, egg, baby foods, prawn, groundnuts or soyabeans, or any formulated foods like cerelac or semovita, pepper or gari water. Your baby will be healthier, stronger and protected from diahorrea sickness if you delay giving foods until after the first 6 months of their life."By now, your baby is growing faster and faster, and should be getting much stronger. If you place them on their belly, they may stretch their arms and legs out and bend the back. When placed on the back, they might lift their head and shoulders. Your baby may even sit up for a small time without your help. Make sure that where they are playing is safe and if possible put pillows around them for cushion if they fall over.  Let them play while laying on the belly on a clean mat on the ground. Lifting the head and chest up to see toys or your face helps make the neck muscles stronger and develops the head control needed for sitting up.  This month, use feeding time to cuddle, hold, and love your baby --  soon they will only want to wiggle away from you. For now clapping your hands for them or giving them something safe and clean to hold can be fun for your baby and helps them learn and grow. ', 1636, 20, 'No Solids', 1, '2014-06-24 01:06:30', '2014-07-06 16:18:35'),
(73, 'fyl-voice-en-21', 2, 'voice', 'English', 'Evil Spirits do not make your baby sick.  Malaria, diahorrea diseases, pneumonia and other fevers are all medical problems which require proper medical attention.  Traditional medicines and herbs are not good for a young baby. If baby has a fever, is not interested in eating, not sucking well at the breast, or spitting up with force, or their eyes or skin look yellow, do not wait to take them to the clinic. Also, if your baby is coughing, has trouble breathing, seems weak or overly sleepy there is something wrong. With a small baby it is difficult to know exactly  what is causing fever or weakness, so it is best to take your baby straight away to the clinic. Early treatment can save your baby''s life.', 709, 21, 'Warning signs', 1, '2014-06-24 01:06:30', '2014-07-06 16:18:35'),
(74, 'fyl-voice-en-22', 2, 'voice', 'English', 'Your period can come anytime from now.  Remember you will ovulate first and can get pregnant before you see your period again. Family planning gives you the choice of when to have your next child. Spacing your children allows you to give each of your children the time they deserve to grow well. It also gives your family time to financially prepare for more children. Taking a family planning method does not make you go outside of your marriage. And using a family planning method now does not cause you to be ill with your next pregnancy. Every woman responds differently to different methods like the pill, IUD, injections or condoms. If the first method you choose does not go well with you, don?t give up on finding a method that does. There are many choices that are safe while you are still breastfeeding and one will work well for you. Speak with your doctor or midwife to help you make the best choice.', 912, 22, 'Family Planning', 1, '2014-06-24 01:06:30', '2014-07-06 16:18:35'),
(75, 'fyl-voice-en-23', 2, 'voice', 'English', 'Malaria can kill your little one. Be sure that  you and your baby sleep under an insecticide treated mosquito net. Be sure that evening time and early dawn your baby is protected from mosquitos by dressing them in something light that covers their legs, feet and arms. Remember to keep your room mosquito free with sprays or by burning coils.  Also clearing bushes around the house, and covering water containers will help control mosquitos. If baby has a fever, is not interested in eating, not sucking well, or spitting up with force, or their eyes or skin look yellow, do not wait to take them to the clinic. Traditional medicines and herbs are not good for babies. Early treatment can save your baby''s life.', 711, 23, 'Malaria', 1, '2014-06-24 01:06:30', '2014-07-06 16:18:35'),
(76, 'fyl-voice-en-24', 2, 'voice', 'English', 'Your baby may have a first tooth by now, but if not they are coming, don?t worry. Teeth come one after another, first the bottom front ones, then the top two middle ones, then the ones along the sides and back. But it can take until the age of 3 years before your baby has all their teeth. Teething can be painful, making your baby a little bit difficult to manage. Some signs that your baby is teething are red, swollen gums, rubbing the ear on the side the tooth is coming, drooling, not sleeping or feeding well, and wanting to bite or suck on anything that comes close to their mouth. Letting your baby suck on your well washed finger can help ease the pain.  Some babies suffer fever or diarrhoea before a tooth comes up, but teething does not cause sickness. If your baby has a fever or diarrhoea, it can be because of so many things so even if you think it is only because of teething, take your baby to clinic to be sure.  ', 931, 24, 'Teething', 1, '2014-06-24 01:06:30', '2014-07-06 16:18:35'),
(77, 'fyl-voice-en-25', 2, 'voice', 'English', 'As your little one is getting their teeth you don''t need to stop breastfeeding.  Babies food needs are mainly met by breastmilk for the first full year of life.  It is not possible in fact for a baby to bite with the first two teeth that come out on the bottom, because their tongue covers the teeth when they are latched on correctly.  But as more teeth come your baby may want to bite down to ease their painful gums.  Your baby doesn''t mean to hurt you.  If your baby bites try to stay calm.  Don''t beat your baby, but stop feeding, look them in the eye and say no! Most babies don''t like being taken from the breast when they are trying to feed, so this usually works well. Then try again to feed.  Most mothers find that their baby stops biting when they do this.  Sometimes your baby may fall asleep at the end of a feeding and bite you without knowing  what they have done, so watch your baby during the feed and remove them from your breast before they fall asleep.  Also, if your baby looks like they are about to bite, put your little finger into the corner of the mouth between the gums so they bite your finger and not your breast. Your baby will soon learn not to bite. Breastmilk is still very important for the protection, growth and development of your baby so keep at it.', 1288, 25, 'Biting nipples', 1, '2014-06-24 01:06:30', '2014-07-06 16:18:35'),
(78, 'fyl-voice-en-26', 2, 'voice', 'English', 'Congratulations! It has not been easy but you and your baby have made it to 6 months. In the 6th month your precious little one should be growing well and should still be putting on weight. Your baby  may even be crawling already. This month your baby needs to attend clinic even if your baby doesn?t have any problems.  Your baby''s weight and length of their body will be measured and charted, and they will be given a dose of Vitamin A to help prevent low blood. The doctor will also make sure all immunizations are up to date, so that your baby is protected from diseases. Make sure you remember to take your baby?s health book. Going to clinic this month gives you the chance to ask any questions you may have about how to make sure your baby stays healthy and can be a good time to discuss family planning if you haven?t already done so."By 6 months your baby is ready for some additional foods along with breastmilk. Your baby is learning and as with all new skills, chewing and swallowing takes practice. Rushing or force feeding leads to chocking or vomiting. Thick foods are also difficult to swallow. Babies this age only eat small mouthfuls, so giving a small amount on the tip of a spoon will help your baby swallow easily.  It is best to feed your baby in a quiet place and take your time.   Koko/porridge should be made rich by adding powdered fish, or beans and a teaspoon of palm oil or groundnut paste.  Also give a small amount of mashed soft fruit like pawpaw or bananas in the day.  When making koko/porridge use clean water and boil food well to kill germs that cause sickness.  Your 6 month old baby will probably not eat more than 1 stew ladle of porridge at a meal, and should be fed two times a day in addition to breastfeeding any other time baby is hungry day and night.  It is important to continue breast feeding for the nutrients, protein,and protection that breast milk provides your baby. ', 1921, 26, 'Vitamin A /Clinic', 1, '2014-06-24 01:06:30', '2014-07-06 16:18:35'),
(79, 'fyl-voice-en-27', 2, 'voice', 'English', 'By 6 months your baby is ready for some additional foods along with breastmilk. Your baby is learning and as with all new skills, chewing and swallowing takes practice. Rushing or force feeding leads to choking or vomiting. Thick foods are also difficult to swallow. Babies this age only eat small mouthfuls, so giving a small amount on the tip of a spoon will help your baby swallow easily.  It is best to feed your baby in a quiet place and take your time.   Pap should be made rich by adding powdered fish, or beans and a teaspoon of palm oil or groundnut paste.  Also give a small amount of mashed soft fruit like pawpaw or bananas in the day.  When making pap use clean water and boil food well to kill germs that cause sickness.  Your 6 month old baby will probably not eat more than 1 stew ladle of food at a meal, and should be fed two times a day in addition to breastfeeding any other time baby is hungry day and night.  It is important to continue breast feeding for the nutrients, protein,and protection that breast milk provides your baby. ', 1053, 27, 'Introducing foods/safety', 1, '2014-06-24 01:06:30', '2014-07-06 16:18:35'),
(80, 'fyl-voice-en-28', 2, 'voice', 'English', 'You know your baby better than anyone so trust yourself if you feel your baby is not well and needs to go to the clinic. Here are a few warning signs that your child is not well: Signs of dehydration, including a dry mouth, lack of tears, sunken fontanelle, (the soft spot on the top of their head) and less than six wet nappies a day.  A fever or if your baby can not or does not want to breastfeed.  Vomiting after eating, or vomiting with great force or a rash that doesn?t fade when the skin is pressed. Sleeping more than usual or too much crying. Trouble  breathing. A swollen belly. Blood or bile (a green substance) in the vomit. Make sure you have immunized baby to help protect them from sickness, and that you are still giving breastmilk to keep your baby healthy, For a fever or signs of dehydration start ORS straight away at home and take the child to clinic without delay.  You can get ORS from your clinic or pharmacy or ask at the clinic how to make it at home.', 978, 28, 'When to go to clinic', 1, '2014-06-24 01:06:30', '2014-07-06 16:18:35'),
(81, 'fyl-voice-en-29', 2, 'voice', 'English', 'While every child develops and learns at their own pace, by 6 months your baby should be able to do some of the following;  Turn towards sounds and voices, copy sounds they hear, blow bubbles from their mouth, roll from back to front or front to back, and might even say mama or baba.  If your baby is not doing any of these things as yet it may mean that there is a problem.  If you have not been to your baby?s 6 month clinic appointment take them this week, so the doctor can make sure that your baby is developing properly and any problems can be addressed early.  This will ensure that your baby has the best chance of growing up well.', 640, 29, 'Milestones', 1, '2014-06-24 01:06:30', '2014-07-06 16:18:35'),
(82, 'fyl-voice-en-30', 2, 'voice', 'English', 'As your baby grows, so do their food needs. At 7 months your baby will now need 3 meals a day as well as breast feeding.  Breastfeeding still gives your baby protection from certain sickness and provides nutrition that keeps your baby growing strong and healthy.   Babies need protein, (such as meat, fish, eggs, or beans), vegetables (such as Ewedu or okro) and fruit.    Your baby will eat much of the same foods as they did at 6 months but you may add more kinds of foods, mashed chicken or fish, well cooked eggs, mashed liver, and fruits like mango, orange, pawpaw, pineapple and avocado pear are all good. The food can be mashed a bit less than last month.  Giving soft foods that are easy to pick up, like sliced banana are good for your baby to practice self feeding. There are a few things you should avoid giving your baby. Your baby can choke on whole groundnuts, and honey has germs that can make your baby sick. Tea and coffee contain things that prevent your baby?s body from being able to make use of iron that is in his food which causes low blood in your baby. ', 1078, 30, 'Food types', 1, '2014-06-24 01:06:30', '2014-07-06 16:18:35'),
(83, 'fyl-voice-en-31', 2, 'voice', 'English', 'Now that your baby is moving around more, it may be more difficult to keep them covered up, but you still need to protect them from mosquito bites in the evening and early dawn.  Light clothes that cover their feet, legs and arms will protect them when they are awake and making sure they sleep under an insecticide treated mosquito net during naps and at night will also help keep them safe from malaria.  Remember that malaria is not the only sickness that causes a fever, weakness, diahorrea and vomiting.  If your child has any of these problems, start ORS at home and go to the clinic straight away to get proper medical attention.  It can mean the difference between life and death for your baby.', 702, 31, 'Malaria', 1, '2014-06-24 01:06:30', '2014-07-06 16:18:35'),
(84, 'fyl-voice-en-32', 2, 'voice', 'English', ' By now you have settled into taking good care of your little one, but are you taking care of yourself? It is best to continue breastfeeding until baby is two years of age, but if you are not eating well this will be difficult for you. You may be feeling too tired or fall sick easy.  While breastfeeding you need to be sure that you are eating protein (like meat, chicken, beans, or eggs), vegetables (tomatos, greens, okro), and some fruit.  Continuing to breastfeed in the night and between your baby?s small meals keeps them healthy and growing strong. Be aware that you can get pregnant even if your period has not started back and if you have seen your period, you definitely can get pregnant.  Be sure you have been to the family planning clinic and have chosen one of the many methods available like the pill, IUD, condoms, or injections to be sure that you don?t get pregnant again too soon. If for any reason you do find yourself pregnant again too soon, speak with your midwife regarding your options. Getting the proper medical advice is far safer than using herbs or other traditional medicines which can cause problems now or with future pregnancies.', 1164, 32, 'Mamas Health', 1, '2014-06-24 01:06:30', '2014-07-06 16:18:35'),
(85, 'fyl-voice-en-33', 2, 'voice', 'English', 'As you baby is now eating solid foods it is easier for them to get cases of diahorrea.  To start treating diahorrea at home you can use Zinc and Oral Rehydration Salts.  For your baby older than 6 months dissolve 20mg tablet in a small amount of clean boiled water or breast milk and give to your baby.  Give once a day for 14 days even if the diarrhea stops earlier.  For ORS put one sachet of ORS in a clean bowl and add one beer bottle or two mineral bottles full of clean boiled water and mix well.  Give this to the child while you prepare to go to the clinic.  You may also give clean boiled water, rice water, or garri water in addition to the ORS. If your baby is vomiting everything, refuses to drink or eat, is weak or limp or has blood in the stool you must rush to the clinic immediately for further medical attention. Your baby can die from dehydration caused by diahorrea.', 886, 33, 'ORS/Zinc', 1, '2014-06-24 01:06:30', '2014-07-06 16:18:35'),
(86, 'fyl-voice-en-34', 2, 'voice', 'English', 'If you haven?t started already you may now feel ready to start having sexual relations with your husband again. If you haven?t started a family planning method yet, you should use a condom. Remember that condoms not only protect you from getting pregnant, but protect you from HIV and other sexually transmitted infections. Remember that you may get pregnant again even if you are not ready. If you do find yourself pregnant again too soon, seek advice from your midwife or doctor at the clinic. If for any reason your pregnancy is terminated outside of a medical clinic make sure you go to your midwife or doctor to see that all is well.  ', 640, 34, 'Family Planning', 1, '2014-06-24 01:06:30', '2014-07-06 16:18:35'),
(87, 'fyl-voice-en-35', 2, 'voice', 'English', 'A healthy 8 month old needs to eat meals 3 times a day, as well as breastfeeding day and night . Your baby should eat one soup ladle of food (mashed yam, agidi, mashed plantain, ogi) and one stew ladle of stew that has mashed fish, meat, chicken or beans in it.  At each meal your baby should also take  2 tablespoons of mashed fruit or vegetable.  It is best that the main caregiver feeds baby, but if your baby eats best when a particular person feeds them you should allow. If your baby refuses to eat it may not mean that they are not hungry, but maybe they do not like the taste of the food. Be patient and keep trying to offer your baby the food. If they still refuse try changing the food by adding different things to change the taste or change the thickness.  Forcing or rushing feeding can easily cause your baby to choke, or learn that eating is not pleasant.   If your baby is not well, breastfeed plenty and feed smaller meals more times in a day to help them get better quickly. When your baby is better add one extra meal a day for 2 weeks so they can regain strength lost from being sick. ', 1105, 35, 'Food types', 1, '2014-06-24 01:06:30', '2014-07-06 16:18:35'),
(88, 'fyl-voice-en-36', 2, 'voice', 'English', 'By now, you may have already told your baby that the telephone is not a toy, not to throw things, or not to pull your hair. At this age your baby may start to test your authority by not following your simple instructions. They are not being naughty or willful ? just curious. They can not remember things you tell them for more than a few seconds at a time. Babies at this age are learning from everything they see and touch and like to pick up and touch everything. It is not good to beat your baby, the best  is to say "no" and then give them something else to play with that is safe.  Keep sharp objects like knives, cutlass, nails, used razor blades tin cans, pieces of glass and mirror away from the play areas. Babies must not ever be put down to play in cooking areas or near lanterns or candles, as burns are a main cause of accidents for little ones. Keep your baby safe by making sure that someone is carefully watching at all times.', 943, 36, 'Milestones', 1, '2014-06-24 01:06:30', '2014-07-06 16:18:35'),
(89, 'fyl-voice-en-37', 2, 'voice', 'English', 'Your husband or family could be telling you that you should have another child or that taking family planning is not good.  Getting pregnant again now can cause you to bleed too much at your next delivery, which can cause you to loose your womb or even cause your death. There are many options when it comes to family planning, like pills, injections (Depo Provera) or an intra-uterine device (implant). Women can have different reactions to family planning methods but there will be a choice for you that works well.  Attend the clinic to get family planning counseling and choose a method that will work for you.', 614, 37, 'Family Planning', 1, '2014-06-24 01:06:30', '2014-07-06 16:18:35'),
(90, 'fyl-voice-en-38', 2, 'voice', 'English', 'Coughs and colds are common in children and usually end without needing medication, But in babies coughs can be serious. Left untreated colds or coughs can turn into pneumonia which can be deadly for your baby. Watch and listen to your baby as they breathe.  If the lower part of the chest sucks in when the child takes a breath or if the belly is moving in and out when they breathe, or your baby sounds like they are snoring but are not asleep your baby is in trouble and needs to see the doctor straight.  You can help prevent pneumonia by protecting your baby from breathing in smoke.  The smoke from tobacco, cooking fires, burning rubbish, and fires to clear land are all dangerous for your little ones growing lungs. If the doctor gives baby medicine to take make sure you understand the directions very well and follow them carefully.  Complete the whole course of medicine.  Be sure to continue breastfeeding. Breastmilk helps your baby get better quick and is the only food they require.  ', 999, 38, 'Coughs/ colds', 1, '2014-06-24 01:06:30', '2014-07-06 16:18:35');
