(91, 'fyl-voice-en-39', 2, 'voice', 'English', 'Now is the week to immunize your baby against measles and yellow fever.  Measles is one of the 9 childhood killers and is extremely dangerous for children that are not eating well.  Measles spread very fast and causes severe diarrhea.   Signs of measles are fever and a rash that have lasted more than 3 days along with a cough, runny nose or red eyes. Measles can cause death. Yellow fever also puts a baby''s life at risk. It is spread by mosquitos and signs of yellow fever are the same as malaria, which are, fever, red eyes, vomiting and not wanting to eat. If any of your children have these symptoms take them straight to the health centre. Immunizations are free at government health centres and only work if given before the disease strikes so it is important to immunize on time.   If your baby gets a small rash from the injection, or a slight fever continue to breastfeed often to help them feel better quick.  Breastfeeding protects baby from sickness and disease, but immunizations protect baby from childhood killers. Make sure that all your baby?s immunizations are to date.', 1089, 39, 'Measles/yellow fever', 1, '2014-06-24 01:08:18', '2014-07-06 16:18:35'),
(92, 'fyl-voice-en-40', 2, 'voice', 'English', 'Keeping your house environment clean and washing your hands keeps the whole family safe from diarrhea and other sickness.  When changing nappies, all faeces should be disposed of in a latrine or toilet, or buried. If you have washed faeces off nappies in a bucket of water, the water should be thrown far away from the house, cooking areas, and away from where other children play. Always wash your hands with soap and water before feeding your child, after changing babies nappies, after toileting, before handling any food, cooking or eating. Babies now also like to put their own hands and anything they can grab into their mouth, so clean their hands often and watch that your baby doesn''t pick rubbish or anything else from the ground to put in their mouth. Don?t be afraid to share what you have learned about handwashing with others in your household. A clean house and clean hands will protect your new precious gift, and the whole family from sickness.  ', 963, 40, 'Handwashing for family', 1, '2014-06-24 01:08:18', '2014-07-06 16:18:35'),
(93, 'fyl-voice-en-41', 2, 'voice', 'English', 'By now your baby probably has some teeth and likes chewing.  They also like to start using their fingers to feed themselves small pieces of food. Snack or (something small between meals) is a good time to let your baby practice feeding themselves.  Your baby still needs to be fed three times a day and now you need to add one snack. This gives the extra energy needed to grow strong.    Now each meal should contain the following: 1 soup ladle of staple (rice, yam, ogi, sweet potato) and one stew ladle of stew/thick soup that has a bit of mashed fish, meat or beans, egg or agushi.  Another option is 2 soup ladles of thick Pap which has 1 teaspoon of palm oil/groundnut paste and fish or bean powder added to be sure your baby gets enough protien. Each meal should have 2 tablespoons of mashed fruit or vegetables. Take time when picking a snack for your baby so that it is not sweet.  Toffees and sweet biscuits are not good snacks.  A banana, pawpaw, poofpof or roasted plantain is a good snack. It?s important to continue breastfeeding between meals but breastfeeding is no longer a substitute for a meal or snack. ', 1122, 41, 'Food types/self feeding', 1, '2014-06-24 01:08:18', '2014-07-06 16:18:35'),
(94, 'fyl-voice-en-42', 2, 'voice', 'English', 'Your baby is growing and may even say 1 or 2 words, but may also still cry a lot.  This doesn?t mean that your baby is bad, it is just that they really have no other way to tell you what they need. By now you probably recognize different types of crying depending on what your baby is trying to tell you. It may be that they are saying they have a wet nappy, are hungry, are tired, or just need some attention. Some people may tell you that you are spoiling your child by playing with them & attending to their crying, but babies at this age cannot be spoiled. Spoiled children have learned to use negative behaviour to get what they want. Your baby is too young to do this. You may find if you give attention to them when they cry, they will actually cry less. Setting limits is necessary but giving baby love & attention will build a trust bond that lasts forever', 865, 42, 'Crying babies', 1, '2014-06-24 01:08:18', '2014-07-06 16:18:35'),
(95, 'fyl-voice-en-43', 2, 'voice', 'English', 'Now that your baby is eating prepared foods and they unfortunately have more chance of getting diarrhoea.  If your child has three or more watery stools in a row your child has diarrhea and should go to the clinic. You can start ORS at home using one sachet from the pharmacy. Mix the sachet with one big beer bottle, or two mineral bottles of clean boiled water.  Along with the ORS you may dissolve a zinc  tablet  in a little bit of clean water and give once a day for 14 days. Use 10mg Zinc tablet for children under 6 months and 20mg for children over 6 months. You can also give clean boiled water, rice water, pap, or coconut water in addition to starting ORS and Zinc. If your child is vomiting everything, is very weak or you notice blood in the stool your child is in serious danger and must go to the clinic straight away. ', 834, 43, 'ORS/Zinc', 1, '2014-06-24 01:08:18', '2014-07-06 16:18:35'),
(96, 'fyl-voice-en-44', 2, 'voice', 'English', 'Malaria can kill your little one. Be sure that  you and your baby sleep under an insecticide treated mosquito net. Be sure that evening time and early dawn your baby is protected from mosquitos by dressing them in something light that covers their legs, feet and arms. Remember to keep your room mosquito free with sprays or by burning coils.  Also clearing bushes around the house, and covering water containers will help control mosquitos. If baby has a fever, is not interested in eating, or spitting up with force, or their eyes or skin look yellow, do not wait to take them to the clinic. Traditional medicines and herbs are not good for babies and not all malaria medicines from the pharmacy are right for babies. Early treatment can save your baby''s life.', 762, 44, 'Malaria', 1, '2014-06-24 01:08:18', '2014-07-06 16:18:35'),
(97, 'fyl-voice-en-45', 2, 'voice', 'English', 'Now your baby likes to pick small pieces of food to feed themselves.  While you should allow them to feed themselves, some things like whole groundnuts,  are just the right size to get stuck in their throat choking them, Also, remember that your baby is using their hands to put things in their mouths so it?s good that you are sure their hands are clean before they go into their mouth. Wash them well with soap and water and wash your hands with soap  and water before preparing food or feeding your baby. This will prevent diarrhoea and worms which are dangerous for all young children. When feeding your baby make sure that spoons, bowls and cups are well washed before using them. Other ways to protect your baby from diarrhoea are to heat food very well before serving, and give your baby fresh food.  Foods that are stored should be covered and in a cool place, but food that has been stored for more than 2 days will make your baby sick.  ', 947, 45, 'Food & hygiene', 1, '2014-06-24 01:08:18', '2014-07-06 16:18:35'),
(98, 'fyl-voice-en-46', 2, 'voice', 'English', 'For your child to be healthy and continue to grow and develop well your baby needs a variety of foods.  Energy foods are like wood for a fire.  They give your child energy to grow. Small amounts of staple foods like ogi, plaintain , pap or eba will give your child energy. Protein foods help your baby develop. Add protein to your child?s meal by adding beans, Ewa, soyabeans, egg, milk, fish, prawns, agushi or meat. Adding 1 teaspoon of palm oil gives your baby Vitamin A to help their eyesight and fight infections. Vitamins and minerals are needed for strong bones and to prevent low blood. Greens like efo, collard greens, ewedu, are all good sources of vitamins and minerals.  Lastly, growing babies need vitamin C from fruits.  Mango, pineapple and banana are good fruits for your child. Giving a variety of foods keeps your child interested in eating and keeps them healthy.', 882, 46, 'feeding', 1, '2014-06-24 01:08:18', '2014-07-06 16:18:35'),
(99, 'fyl-voice-en-47', 2, 'voice', 'English', 'As your baby starts to take different kinds of foods, the stools will become thicker, darker and a lot more smelly. Your baby can also suffer constipation.  You may see them pushing hard as they try to pass stools, or they don?t make any faeces for more than 2 days and the faeces look like small, dry pellets. Constipation causes pain, a tight belly, and your baby may cry easily as they are uncomfortable.  Sometimes you may see blood streaked stools which could be due to anal fissures (tiny cracks in the skin) caused by passing hard stools. Your baby is dehydrated if they are weak, limp, have sunken eyes or a sunken fontanelle. Continue breastfeeding between meals as breastmilk helps to prevent the germs which cause diarrhoea, keeps your child hydrated and the stools soft preventing constipation. If your child becomes dehydrated, start ORS and Zinc at home and go to the clinic without delay. ', 904, 47, 'Constipation/ diarrhoea/ Breastfeeding', 1, '2014-06-24 01:08:18', '2014-07-06 16:18:35'),
(100, 'fyl-voice-en-48', 2, 'voice', 'English', ' Your baby will soon be celebrating their one year birthday.  This is great.  By now your baby should be able to do some of the following things: Say ''dada'' and ''mama'' to the right parent.  Play a clapping game. Stand alone for a couple of seconds, copy others activities, put things into a container, understand simple instructions, drink from a cup, say one word other than mama and dada, or stoop from a standing position. Some children will have delays in a particular area, such as walking, while the rest of their skills continue developing on or ahead of schedule. If that''s the case for your child, it may just mean they are concentrating so hard on talking or understanding that the brain has forgot about walking for a small time. Also, perhaps your child is walking already but does not say anything yet.  As they are learning new things all the time,  they should be encouraged, and praised when they have learned something new or said something new. It will give the child the confidence to keep learning and trying. For all children, boys or girls, playing with them, singing to them, telling them stories, and talking to them helps them learn to think. Don?t be afraid to take your baby to the clinic if  you think something is wrong or you are worried about how your baby is growing.  ', 1301, 48, 'Milestones', 1, '2014-06-24 01:08:18', '2014-07-06 16:18:35'),
(101, 'fyl-voice-en-49', 2, 'voice', 'English', 'At eleven months your baby is starting to eat more food at each feeding. They should still eat 3 times a day and a small snack, between meals.  Breastfeeding when baby wants including in the night time is still important for the extra energy and nutrients.  Your baby can eat many different kinds of food and actually eat better when different foods are offered in the day. Also, your baby should be eating some snacks by themselves, like small pieces of soft fruit.   Sweets, toffees sweet bisquits and minerals are not good for babies. They contain too much sugar, and minerals can give diahorrea. Don?t force your child to eat, and if baby has been ill give foods and breastmilk more often than usual in order to help your baby recover quickly.  If your baby has not been eating, is losing weight, limp or lethargic, hair color is changing, make sure that you take them to the clinic. If you are told that your baby has low blood the doctor can help and may give vitamins to supplement the food you are giving. ', 1014, 49, 'Food types', 1, '2014-06-24 01:08:18', '2014-07-06 16:18:35'),
(102, 'fyl-voice-en-50', 2, 'voice', 'English', 'You may have already started disciplining your child, but here are a few tips about discipline,. First, we need to know that discipline means teaching, not punishing.  Babies play because it is fun, and play is also how they learn and grow. They are not able to understand things like their older brothers or sisters.  Babies don''t yet know right from wrong so they are not trying to be naughty or bad, even if, they seem troublesome . They learn by doing things, and then watching to see what happens and how you or others will react to their behaviour. Like what happens when they turn over their cup of water. Also, babies can not remember things for long so if you told baby not to touch something one day, they may not remember not to touch it the next day. Lastly, all babies learn by copying what they see people do, therefore we need to set  good examples for them to follow. Be patient and try to give baby something else to do when they are doing something you don''t like. ', 983, 50, 'Discipline', 1, '2014-06-24 01:08:18', '2014-07-06 16:18:35'),
(103, 'fyl-voice-en-51', 2, 'voice', 'English', 'At one year your baby needs to go to the clinic, even if they are healthy. The time at the clinic gives you a chance to make sure everything is well with your baby.  It is a good time to ask any questions that you may have, and a time to make sure that all your baby?s immunizations are complete.  Completing all immunizations before one year will make sure that your child is protected from the childhood killers. Make sure you remember to take your baby?s health card with you.  At this clinic visit your baby will be weighed and measured and given another dose of Vitamin A.  If needed, the doctor will give some vitamins to help keep baby growing strong.  Each of your children has a better start at life, if there is more time between your pregnancies, so if you haven?t started a Family planning method yet, use this trip to the clinic to get started. Family planning is good for you and for your family.', 910, 51, 'Clinic', 1, '2014-06-24 01:08:18', '2014-07-06 16:18:35'),
(104, 'fyl-voice-en-52', 2, 'voice', 'English', 'Congratulations! Your baby is now 1 year old.  You have done a great job. Ensuring your baby eats well, gets timely care when they are not well and receives all of their immunizations on schedule is one of the best things you can do for all of your children, so that they grow up strong and healthy .  We hope that the messages have been helpful and that you will be able to share some of what you learned about taking good care of your baby with your friends and family. We also hope that you will be able use the information you have received to ensure that all of the children in your family stay healthy.   ', 611, 52, 'Congratulations', 1, '2014-06-24 01:08:18', '2014-07-06 16:18:35'),
(105, 'preg-sms-en-5', 1, 'sms', 'English', 'When you first realize you are pregnant, you need to go to ANC which is free at many government facilities. If you feel discouraged by the long queue, remember that there is no sacrifice too great for having a healthy pregnancy which ends with a healthy strong baby.  At ANC  1. You will be screened (blood pressure and blood tests) to make sure your body is healthy for a good start. 2. If needed you will receive your tetanus immunization to protect you and your baby.  3. You will be given folic acid and iron tablets to keep you and your baby strong. 3. You will start to get to know the Hospital and nurses that will see you throughout your pregnancy, so you will be more comfortable at delivery time. Every pregnancy is different so you need to be sure you are fine for this one.  It is best to go to ANC 4 times during your pregnancy and our messages will remind you when it is time.', 890, 1, 'ANC', 1, '2014-07-03 11:01:12', '2014-07-06 16:18:35'),
(106, 'preg-sms-en-6', 1, 'sms', 'English', 'Many people believe that people can spiritually harm you or your baby if you go to the hospital for ANC. Problems that come with pregnancy and delivery are medical problems that can be treated by medical professionals.  They are not problems caused by the evil doings of others. Going to ANC as well as PNC within 24 hours after birth provides safety for both you and your newborn baby. Registering at the government hospitals can also help cut costs as ANC consultations are free, although there are some related costs. ', 521, 2, 'Myths/Evil Eye', 1, '2014-07-03 11:01:12', '2014-07-06 16:18:35'),
(107, 'preg-sms-en-7', 1, 'sms', 'English', 'Keeping yourself as healthy as possible is very important right now.  As well as always washing your hands with soap there are a few other easy things you can do to help keep your whole family from getting sick.  When you have prepared food, be sure to cover it to protect it from insects, flies, birds and pets.  Make sure that your food are always cooked until they are very hot right through. Well cooked meat and poultry will not have any pink parts. Wash your greens and salad very well in clean or boiled water before cooking or eating them. If you do get diarrhoea make sure you treat straight away with ORS and zinc which you can buy at the chemical shop. If it continues go to the clinic for treatment.', 711, 3, 'Food Safety', 1, '2014-07-03 11:01:12', '2014-07-06 16:18:35'),
(108, 'preg-sms-en-8', 1, 'sms', 'English', 'The early part of your pregnancy is very important as your baby''s body parts are forming. Eating well ensures that your baby develops properly and that you stay strong for delivery. There is no medical proof that eating certain foods like snail, banana or pineapple, directly affect your babyÆs skin, head or make them drip saliva. Be sure to eat a lot of greens and vegetables such as spinach, garden eggs, okro, and tomatoes.  You need foods which build your body and help your baby too, like groundnut, beans, eggs, beef, fish, soya or chicken. Eating plenty of fresh fruits like oranges, bananas, pineapples, helps your body make good use of the iron you are taking.    ', 674, 4, 'Nutrition', 1, '2014-07-03 11:01:12', '2014-07-06 16:18:35'),
(109, 'preg-sms-en-9', 1, 'sms', 'English', 'Tetanus is a serious sickness which enters the body through a wound like a juke or scratch on the skin. You are at risk for tetanus during and after birth because of the delivery and your baby is at risk because of the cutting of the umbilical cord. You need to get an immunization to protect you and your baby. You will need two jabs through your pregnancy. Getting the first jab early ensures you and your baby are protected. Even if you have been given the jab before you may need another one to be sure you are still safe. The jab for tetanus is called TT and you can always ask your midwife or doctor at the clinic or hospital for more information.', 653, 5, 'Tetanus/ TT Immunization', 1, '2014-07-03 11:06:59', '2014-07-06 16:18:35'),
(110, 'preg-sms-en-10', 1, 'sms', 'English', 'Feeling tired while pregnant is normal in the first few months as your body works hard to grow your baby. As the pregnancy goes on your increased weight can also make you feel tired. Try to rest when you can and try to ask someone you trust to help you with lifting of heavy things and some housework. Also, going out to get some fresh air during the day can help you feel better.', 380, 6, 'Tiredness', 1, '2014-07-03 11:06:59', '2014-07-06 16:18:35'),
(111, 'preg-sms-en-11', 1, 'sms', 'English', 'Going to ANC gives you the best chance at a healthy pregnancy and a healthy baby. If you havenÆt been since you realized you are pregnant, go this week.  If needed you will receive your tetanus immunization to protect you and your baby.  You will be given folic acid and iron tablets to keep you and your baby healthy 3. you have the chance to ask questions about your pregnancy and how your baby is doing. 4. You will get to know the nurses and the hospital so you will be more comfortable when you go to deliver. 5. You can use the time to ask your midwife or doctor about any problems you may be experiencing. Attending 4 ANC visits through your pregnancy help ensure both you and your baby are healthy and safe.', 715, 7, 'ANC', 1, '2014-07-03 11:06:59', '2014-07-06 16:18:35'),
(112, 'preg-sms-en-12', 1, 'sms', 'English', 'Malaria is serious when you are pregnant. It can lead to miscarriage, anaemia or low blood and your baby can be born too small or even dead.  The only cause of malaria is the bite of mosquitos. To protect yourself and your baby always sleep under insecticide treated nets (ITN). Take SP which is a medicine you will get at the clinic at 3 of your 4 ANC visits. Wear light coloured clothes that cover your arms and legs and use mosquito spray or cream for your body.  Fold up your clothes instead of hanging them, so mosquitos canÆt hide in them. Not all malaria tablets are good for your or your baby during pregnancy. If you have a fever, chills, bad headaches or pain in your joints go straight to the clinic to get the correct treatment early which will protect you and your baby.', 783, 8, 'Malaria', 1, '2014-07-03 11:06:59', '2014-07-06 16:18:35'),
(113, 'preg-sms-en-13', 1, 'sms', 'English', 'MEN: Have you taken your wife to the health centre yet?  Getting her to antenatal clinic and planning for the birth of your baby will make sure that your wife delivers safely and your baby has the best start at life. The more you know about the pregnancy, the more helpful you can be to your wife, which can help ease some of the stress of pregnancy. It is also not too early to start putting some money aside each week to save for transport to the delivery facility and the things your wife will need. For the delivery she will need to pack a few things to take to the hospital. Some of the things she will need baby napkins, a few baby dresses, soap, towels, sponge, olive oil and methylated spirt.  She will also need clean clothes for herself, disinfectant like bleach or dettol, and sanitary towels. Start preparing now. It is far safer for your wife and your baby if she delivers at a health facility supervised by qualified health workers.', 946, 9, 'MEN-ANC', 1, '2014-07-03 11:06:59', '2014-07-06 16:18:35'),
(114, 'preg-sms-en-14', 1, 'sms', 'English', 'Bleeding in early pregnancy can happen. You may spot or bleed a little at the time when you would normally have a period. This happens as your baby settles into the womb. It is not always possible to know what caused the bleeding so it is important go to the clinic and tell your midwife or doctor about it when it happens.  Infection of the birth passage or other problems can be the cause and your doctor can help you treat it. If bleeding is heavy or painful you must see the midwife or doctor straight away.', 511, 10, 'Bleeding', 1, '2014-07-03 11:06:59', '2014-07-06 16:18:35'),
(115, 'preg-sms-en-15', 1, 'sms', 'English', 'Your baby''s body parts are all there now but are not yet fully formed. Your baby has hair, and fingernails and in the next three weeks will double in size. It is common to get muscle aches and pains in your belly and womb during pregnancy as your body changes to support your growing baby. Taking traditional medicines for pain, can damage your baby, cause mental problems for your baby, or even cause you to miscarry.  You can help ease the pain by sitting down, putting up your feet on a pillow and relaxing a while and drinking plenty of clean/boiled water during the day.  You need to go to the clinic straight away if you get strong cramps, fever, are shivering or bleeding or if you feel like fainting as this is a sign of something serious.', 747, 11, 'Aches/ traditional med.', 1, '2014-07-03 11:06:59', '2014-07-06 16:18:35'),
(116, 'preg-sms-en-16', 1, 'sms', 'English', 'You and your babyÆs life are far better protected if you deliver at a health facility with qualified health workers. Whether this is your first child or you have delivered before, every labour is different. There is no way to tell what problems may arise once labour starts and things can go very fast. Problems that arise are medical problems, not spiritual and delivering at the health facility ensures that trained medical professionals are there to solve them. The doctors are there to ensure you have a safe delivery and a healthy baby, and all that they do to you is to make sure that everything is fine. Start planning and preparing now by putting some money aside for when the time comes.', 696, 12, 'Facility Delivery', 1, '2014-07-03 11:06:59', '2014-07-06 16:18:35'),
(117, 'preg-sms-en-17', 1, 'sms', 'English', 'Being pregnant is not an illness but sometimes comes with some medical problems which need attention by trained medical professionals. Problems are not caused by evil spirits, evil eye or juju. Eating well, going to your 4 ANC visits to get your TT immunization and malaria medication (SP), and being informed will help you feel less worried and prepare you for the eventual safe delivery of your healthy baby.', 410, 13, 'Spiritualists ', 1, '2014-07-03 11:08:48', '2014-07-06 16:18:35'),
(118, 'preg-sms-en-18', 1, 'sms', 'English', 'When you are pregnant, your body changes and you will see a change in your vaginal discharge. The discharge should be a mild, milk-like discharge that doesn''t smell bad.  It is good to keep your genital area clean by using only soap and water on the outside area only.   If your discharge becomes yellow, brown, green or foul-smelling, itches or burns, you have an infection. Go to the health centre straight away for treatment. Having an infection can be due to the changes in your body while you are pregnant, but having an infection doesnÆt necessarily mean you were unfaithful to your husband. Leaving infections untreated can affect your unborn baby.', 655, 14, 'Vaginal Infections', 1, '2014-07-03 11:08:48', '2014-07-06 16:18:35'),
(119, 'preg-sms-en-19', 1, 'sms', 'English', 'It may seem early to be thinking about delivery time, but it is best to be prepared.  Try to involve your husband or family to help prepare. During pregnancy and childbirth serious problems can come on quickly without warning. You need to know where the closest hospital is and how you will get there at any hour. How will you pay for transportation? Maybe you need to move closer to the health facility as delivery time comes close. Have a contact number for your nurse or doctor, in case of an emergency and to call at the first sign of labour. It may seem less expensive if you deliver outside a hospital, but if you start saving a little money each week for things you will need, your transportation and delivery cost you will be able to take comfort in the fact that you are doing the best for you and your babyÆs safety.', 826, 15, 'Birth Preparedness', 1, '2014-07-03 11:08:48', '2014-07-06 16:18:35'),
(120, 'preg-sms-en-20', 1, 'sms', 'English', 'It is important to eat well during pregnancy so your baby gets all he or she needs to grow well. You may have been told eating certain foods will affect your health or the baby, but there is no medical proof of this. You need to eat foods from three main groups. Energy giving foods to eat are maize, eba, rice, plantain, and yam. Body building foods are beans, ground nuts, meat, chicken, and fish. The third group are protective foods which are fruits and vegetables. Eat plenty of greens like ewedu, other vegetables like tomato, and okro, and fruits like oranges, bananas, and mangoes.', 589, 16, 'Nutrition', 1, '2014-07-03 11:08:48', '2014-07-06 16:18:35'),
(121, 'preg-sms-en-21', 1, 'sms', 'English', 'Tetanus is a serious sickness which enters the body through a wound like a juke or scratch on the skin. You are at risk for tetanus during and after giving birth to your baby.  Your baby is also at risk when the umbilical cord is cut. All pregnant women need to be protected against tetanus. Even if you have been given the jab before you may need another one to be sure you are still protected. Getting the jab when you are pregnant also protects your baby for its first few weeks of life.. The jab for tetanus is called TT and you can always ask at your clinic, for more information to be sure you and your baby are protected.', 628, 17, 'Tetanus', 1, '2014-07-03 11:08:48', '2014-07-06 16:18:35'),
(122, 'preg-sms-en-22', 1, 'sms', 'English', 'Problems during your pregnancy are medical problems and are not caused by bad spirits, or the evil doings of others.  Even if you havenÆt finished your tablets from your last visit, go to your health facility if you are bleeding. It can be the sign of a serious problem with the positioning of your placenta, that puts your baby at risk. Go to your health facility if you get blurry or flashing vision, swelling in your face, hands, feet, or eyes or a bad headache. It may be a sign of a severe complication called pre-eclampsia, and can cause you or your baby to die. Also, go to your health facility if you have a fever or serious vomiting, had a blow to the belly, a sharp pain on one side of your belly or dark yellow or bloody urine.', 738, 18, 'Warning Signs', 1, '2014-07-03 11:08:48', '2014-07-06 16:18:35'),
(123, 'preg-sms-en-23', 1, 'sms', 'English', 'This week you are due to take a medicine called SP to help prevent you from getting malaria. It is only given at your health centre so you need to attend ANC. You will need two more doses later and and we will send you reminder messages. Malaria is caused by mosquitos that bite in the evening, night and early dawn. The best way to prevent malaria is to take your SP, cover up in the evening and dawn and most importantly, sleep under your insecticide treated bed-net. When you register for ANC, most government hospitals give you a big bed net to help keep you and your family safe from malaria. If you have any signs of malaria such as fever chills, shivering, bad headaches, or joint pain get to the health facility immediately for early treatment.', 752, 19, 'SP/ANC', 1, '2014-07-03 11:08:48', '2014-07-06 16:18:35'),
(124, 'preg-sms-en-24', 1, 'sms', 'English', 'MEN:  A baby is a gift from God to both of you. Support your pregnant lady to deliver safely.  This includes financial, physical and emotional support which can be difficult for those with little income. But there is support you can give your lady which does not cost you anything. You can show your wife that you care by going to antenatal clinic with her. You can ask questions about how the delivery will be, and you have time to discuss with the midwife and your wife about what else you can do to help.', 507, 20, 'Men ANC', 1, '2014-07-03 11:08:48', '2014-07-06 16:18:35'),
(125, 'preg-sms-en-25', 1, 'sms', 'English', 'Washing your hands is always very important to prevent worms and sickness and even more important when you are pregnant. Rinsing your hands with water before you eat is not enough to get them clean. Wash your hands with soap to remove the germs that can cause infection. Always wash your hands with soap after toileting, or cleaning a child that has gone to toilet, before and after cooking and before serving food.  Washing your hands with soap will go a long way to prevent you and your whole family from getting sick with typhoid or cholera and from getting worms.', 567, 21, 'Hygiene', 1, '2014-07-03 11:08:48', '2014-07-06 16:18:35'),
(126, 'preg-sms-en-26', 1, 'sms', 'English', 'Most women have low iron levels during pregnancy. Iron is very important because it lets your body do its work of carrying oxygen (air) around to where it needs to go. If you don''t have enough iron you may feel over tired or find it hard to breathe.  Low iron or anaemia is very dangerous for you and your baby. If you have low iron, you face many risks during delivery and your baby can be born too small. Be sure to take iron and folic acid tablets given to you at ANC and eat foods that contain iron like, fish or meat, and green leafy vegetables, and try to take fruits like orange, pineapple or mango to help the iron enter your blood easily.', 647, 22, 'Anemia', 1, '2014-07-03 11:08:48', '2014-07-06 16:18:35'),
(127, 'preg-sms-en-27', 1, 'sms', 'English', 'It is important to drink lots of clean water when you are pregnant to prevent dehydration. If you are not drinking enough water you may feel overly tired or weak, dizzy, or get headaches. Also, your urine will turn dark yellow.  If you drink at least eight glasses or sachets of clean water each day you will help prevent bladder infections, constipation, and piles. If you are having trouble drinking water, you can drink fresh fruit juice. Eating fruits like pineapples and oranges or watermelon can also help keep you from getting dehydrated.  Try to avoid minerals, Coca-Cola, tea and coffee as these can actually dehydrate you. Taking alcohol, even Star or Gulder with milk, will also not only dehydrate you but it can actually affect your unborn baby, so avoid it.', 770, 23, 'Dehydration/Alcohol', 1, '2014-07-03 11:08:48', '2014-07-06 16:18:35'),
(128, 'preg-sms-en-28', 1, 'sms', 'English', 'Well done, you are nearing the end of the second stage of your pregnancy. You may have heard that babies are a gift from God and should be delivered by a spiritualist or at a prayer camp, and not in a health facility. You and your baby''s life are far better protected if you deliver in a health facility. Even if you are young and healthy or you have delivered before, every delivery is different and problems can happen quickly once labour starts. At the health facility any problems with delivery can be solved quickly by medically trained professionals. Actions taken during your delivery are to help you and your baby survive. For your and your babyÆs safety, plan and prepare to deliver at the health facility.', 715, 24, 'Facility Delivery', 1, '2014-07-03 11:08:48', '2014-07-06 16:18:35'),
(129, 'preg-sms-en-29', 1, 'sms', 'English', 'ANC visits make sure that you and your baby are healthy.  In this week''s ANC visit you will be checked for anemia or low blood, and have your blood pressure checked. You will also have a urine test to check for infections or other problems and if you need one you will get a tetanus jab. Your babyÆs size and movements will also be checked to see if all is well.  You will be given more iron and folic acid tablets and a dose of SP to protect you from malaria. Your midwife will talk to you about your birth plans and you will have a chance to ask questions about your pregnancy and your baby.  Going to ANC is one of the best things you can do for a safe healthy pregnancy.', 674, 25, 'ANC/SP', 1, '2014-07-03 11:08:48', '2014-07-06 16:18:35'),
(130, 'preg-sms-en-30', 1, 'sms', 'English', 'Malaria is very dangerous when you are pregnant. It can lead to anaemia or low blood which can cause death during pregnancy or delivery. Malaria can cause your baby to be born too small, or even dead. To help keep you and your baby safe: 1. always sleep under insecticide treated bed nets; 2.protect your skin from mosquito bites by covering up with light colored long sleeves and full length clothes; 3. always fold up your clothes in the room as hanging them gives mosquitos places to hide; 4. spray the room with mosquito spray. If you have any signs of malaria such as fever chills, shivering, bad headaches, or joint pain get to the medical facility immediately for early treatment. Remember not to take any medicines that have not been given to you by your doctor or midwife as they can cause problems with your pregnancy or for your baby.', 845, 26, 'Malaria', 1, '2014-07-03 11:08:48', '2014-07-06 16:18:35'),
(131, 'preg-sms-en-31', 1, 'sms', 'English', 'MEN: Your wife is getting closer to delivery time and it is best to be prepared for when your baby comes. Mommy can''t do everything by herself, so it is time for husbands and other family to help. Do you have transportation arranged for when the time comes and money for it? Should mommy move closer to the health facility for the last stage of the pregnancy? Do you have the contact details for the doctor or midwife for when labour starts or for any emergency? Have you registered at ANC? Do you have some money set aside for delivery? You will need baby napkins, cloths for mother, soap, antiseptic (Bleach or Dettol) olive oil, cord clamp for your baby, and anything else your doctor tells you to bring. The delivery time is near so it is not to early to be prepared.', 771, 27, 'MEN/ Birth Preparedness', 1, '2014-07-03 11:08:48', '2014-07-06 16:18:35'),
(132, 'preg-sms-en-32', 1, 'sms', 'English', 'A baby that is born early, before 36 weeks of pregnancy is called premature.  Premature babies can be healthy although a bit small.  If your baby is born early there are a few things you must do to be sure they grow strong : 1) don''t bathe premature babies, just wipe them with a clean cloth so they don''t get cold; 2) carry your baby wrapped between your breasts with a cloth (instead of on your back), as keeping your baby next to your breasts will keep them warm and happy; 3) applying shea butter on their body will also help keep them warm; 4) breastfeed immediately after birth (within one hour) and do not give anything but breast milk for the first 6 months. Water and other food is not needed and is dangerous. Breastmilk has everything your baby needs to grow strong.', 777, 28, 'Premature Babies', 1, '2014-07-03 11:09:51', '2014-07-06 16:18:35'),
(133, 'preg-sms-en-33', 1, 'sms', 'English', 'Leg cramps or sharp sudden pains in the lower leg that last a few minutes are common in this stage of pregnancy.  As your baby grows it puts pressure on your nerves and veins, and the extra weight  tires your muscles.  You can help prevent cramps by making sure you drink plenty water in the day.  Also if you get a cramp try rubbing the area gently or apply firm pressure over the painful area. You can also stretch the leg by straightening the knee and bend your foot upward.  This will hurt at first but the pain should then go away.  You can also try getting up and walking, or stand on your toes.  If the pain doesn''t go away, the leg is swollen, or your toes feel numb or tingle, report to the your nearest health centre straight away as this is a sign of a blood clot which can be very dangerous.', 803, 29, 'Leg Cramps', 1, '2014-07-03 11:09:51', '2014-07-06 16:18:35'),
(134, 'preg-sms-en-34', 1, 'sms', 'English', 'You are getting closer to delivery time and your body is changing a lot. You may feel fine but there are a few things you must report to your midwife or doctor if you feel. Fever, bleeding, sharp one-sided pain in your belly is a sign of something serious. If your baby''s movements in your womb have slowed down or stopped there is a problem. If you have blurry or flashing vision, severe swelling in your face or hands or around your eyes it is a sign of pre-eclampsia which means you need medical attention straight away. Also if you are suddenly more thirsty and urinating more it can be a sign of pregnancy induced diabetes. You need to be tested. Try not to worry, these are medical problems and you can do a lot to help yourself and your baby by going to the health facility without delay.', 795, 30, 'Warning Signs', 1, '2014-07-03 11:09:51', '2014-07-06 16:18:35'),
(135, 'preg-sms-en-35', 1, 'sms', 'English', 'Labour can start anytime day or night. When labour starts the stomach muscles will tighten and harden, and this usually comes with some pain. The cramp-like feeling will then start to come more often, get stronger, last longer and be more painful. You may also see what is called a ôshowö which is when a clear, jelly-like clump will come out.  If your water breaks or you are having contractions you need to call your midwife or doctor right away. The best way to protect you and your child is to deliver in a medical facility with qualified health professionals. Taking time at home can mean the difference between life and death for you or your baby.   DonÆt wait for a problem to arise, as soon as you think you are in labour, go to the delivery facility. This ensures that any problems with the delivery or your newborn baby are properly addressed before it is too late.', 875, 31, 'Labour Signs', 1, '2014-07-03 11:09:51', '2014-07-06 16:18:35'),
(136, 'preg-sms-en-36', 1, 'sms', 'English', 'While your baby is in your belly everything they need is passed from you to them through the umbilical cord attached to your baby''s belly. When your baby is born, the cord is cut freeing mommy from baby. Once the cord is cut there is a wound that looks like a tree stump. Keep this wound dry and clean. Don''t put anything on it like soap, shea butter, traditional herbs or even surgical spirit. Make sure that  the baby napkins don''t rub or cover the wound. Don''t force the stump of the cord to fall off as it will fall by itself in 10-12 days. Infections of the stump are serious and can cause your baby to die. If you see any redness or pus in or around the wound, see doctor straight away.', 692, 32, 'Cord care', 1, '2014-07-03 11:09:51', '2014-07-06 16:18:35'),
(137, 'preg-sms-en-37', 1, 'sms', 'English', 'A baby that is born early, before 36 weeks of pregnancy is called premature.  Premature babies can be healthy although a bit small.  If your baby is born early there are a few things you must do to be sure they grow strong : 1) don''t bathe premature babies, just wipe them with a clean cloth so they don''t get cold; 2) carry your baby wrapped between your breasts with a cloth (instead of on your back), as keeping your baby next to your breasts will keep them warm and happy; 3) applying shea butter on their body will also help keep them warm; 4) breastfeed immediately after birth (within one hour) and do not give anything but breast milk for the first 6 months. Water and other food is not needed and is dangerous. Breastmilk has everything your baby needs to grow strong.', 777, 33, 'Premature Babies', 1, '2014-07-03 11:09:51', '2014-07-06 16:18:35'),
(138, 'preg-sms-en-38', 1, 'sms', 'English', 'As soon as your baby is born you can start protecting them from infection and sickness. The best way to do this is for you to breastfeed. Start breastfeeding as soon as your baby is born. This can be done even before you and your baby are bathed. Just wipe your baby and your breasts with a clean cloth and put baby to the breast. The first milk from your breast is thick and yellowish and is called colostrum. It is the best milk for your baby to get straight away as it has protein and other important infection fighting agents. Having your baby to the breast straight after birth also keeps baby warm, so they donÆt loose valuable energy needed to stay strong. Breastfeeding your baby in the first hour of his or her life gives your baby the best chance at a long healthy life.', 780, 34, 'EBF/ 1st feed immediately', 1, '2014-07-03 11:09:51', '2014-07-06 16:18:35'),
(139, 'preg-sms-en-39', 1, 'sms', 'English', 'This week you need to go to clinic for your last ANC visit before delivery. If needed, you will get your last dose of SP to protect you from malaria. You can start labor anytime from now so this visit is important to be sure all is well.  Are you prepared when the time comes?  Do you have transportation arranged and money for it? Do you know who will go with you? Are you sure of which health facility you will be delivering at?  Do you have the contact details for the doctor or midwife for when labour starts or for any emergency? Make sure you have what you will need for delivery. Some of the things you need are baby napkins, cord clamp for the baby,  sanitary towels for mother, soap, antiseptic (bleach, Dettol) methylated spirit and olive oil, towels. The delivery time is near so be prepared.', 803, 35, 'SP/ANC/ birth preparedness', 1, '2014-07-03 11:09:51', '2014-07-06 16:18:35'),
(140, 'preg-sms-en-40', 1, 'sms', 'English', 'If for any reason your baby was delivered outside a medical facility, you need to visit the postnatal clinic (PNC) within 24 hours of delivery, even if you and your baby seem healthy. This is very important to make sure all is well.  Visiting the clinic with your baby gives you time to talk to the nurse or doctor about breastfeeding, caring for the umbilical cord stump, and danger signs that your baby is not well.  Your baby will also receive immunizations to prevent tuberculosis and polio.  You will get a dose of vitamin A to help you recover from the delivery. An early first visit with your baby to the clinic is one of the best things you can do to be sure your baby has a good healthy start at life.', 710, 36, '1st PNC Visit', 1, '2014-07-03 11:09:51', '2014-07-06 16:18:35'),
(141, 'preg-sms-en-41', 1, 'sms', 'English', 'When your baby joins us in the outside world, they need time to adjust, especially if they are born premature.  For the first 24 hours of life, your baby should be kept warm and dry.  Do not bathe your new born baby in the first 24 hours. Bathing causes your baby to loose body heat. When your newborn is cold, they loose needed energy. This causes many problems for your new baby. Your brand new baby only needs to be wiped with a clean soft cloth, be held by you, and be given your breast as soon as they are born, so they can stay warm, dry and healthy.', 556, 37, 'Warm Baby', 1, '2014-07-03 11:09:51', '2014-07-06 16:18:35'),
(142, 'preg-sms-en-42', 1, 'sms', 'English', 'Breastfed babies are healthier, stronger and suffer fewer sicknesses than babies that are given other foods or drinks. Put your baby to your breast immediately after delivery even if you feel tired or weak.  The right positioning during feeding is important for your baby to eat well and will ensure your baby is satisfied.  Your baby''s whole body should be turned to face you, and you and your baby should be belly to belly. Signs that your baby is feeding well are: their chin is touching your breast, more of the dark skin around your nipple can be seen above your baby''s mouth than below it, your baby takes long, deep sucks, and you don''t feel any pain in the nipple. Breast milk alone will satisfy your baby and is all your baby needs to eat for the first 6 months of life.', 779, 38, 'EBF/ 1st feed immediately', 1, '2014-07-03 11:09:51', '2014-07-06 16:18:35'),
(143, 'preg-sms-en-43', 1, 'sms', 'English', 'If for any reason your baby was born outside of the medical facility, be sure you go to the clinic with your baby within 24 hours of the delivery to be sure everything is ok. Even if you feel fine and your baby seems well it is important to go. Because of the amount of blood lost during delivery you can become anemic or have very low blood. You will be given a dose of vitamin A, and another one when you go to the PNC visit 2 days after the birth.  Your baby will get their first immunizations which are very important to protect your baby against polio and tuberculosis.', 574, 39, '1st PNC', 1, '2014-07-03 11:09:51', '2014-07-06 16:18:35'),
(144, 'preg-sms-en-44', 1, 'sms', 'English', 'Once your baby is born there are a few things to watch for to be sure they are healthy. If you see any of these signs take your baby to the clinic straight away.  Don''t wait until it is too late.  1) Fever or high temperature. 2) If your baby is having problems breathing or breathing very hard. 3) If your baby is not sucking as well as before, doesn''t want to eat, or spits up with force. 4) If  your baby becomes weak or limp. 5) If your baby''s feces become hard and dry or is watery.  Most babies are healthy most of the time but it is very important to take your baby to the clinic straight away if something is wrong. It can be the difference between life and death.', 672, 40, 'Warning Signs for Baby', 1, '2014-07-03 11:09:51', '2014-07-06 16:18:35'),
(145, 'preg-sms-en-45', 1, 'sms', 'English', 'Malaria is caused by the bite of mosquitos, and can kill your newborn baby. Be sure that you and your baby sleep under an insecticide treated mosquito net. Be sure that evening time and early dawn your baby is protected from mosquitos by dressing them in something light that covers their legs, feet and arms. Remember to keep your room mosquito free with sprays or by burning coils.  Clearing bushes around the house and covering water containers will also help control mosquitos. If your baby has a fever, is not interested in eating, not sucking well, or spitting up with force, do not wait  and take them to the clinic. Early treatment can save your baby''s life.', 666, 41, 'Malaria', 1, '2014-07-03 11:09:51', '2014-07-06 16:18:35'),
(146, 'preg-sms-en-46', 1, 'sms', 'English', 'By now you should be getting used to breastfeeding but you may find that your breasts are painful.  This is common in the beginning and it will pass as your breasts adjust to making the right amount of milk for your baby. The best thing to do is to continue breast feeding  Skipping a feeding will cause your breasts have too much milk and they will be even more painful.  Feed whenever you or your baby wants. You should feed at least 10 times in one day and night. If your baby sleeps a lot wake them up to feed if you feel your breasts are full.  Make sure your baby is well positioned for feeding and is well attached with the nipple and has a lot of the dark area around the nipple in their mouth.  If you need help or the breasts are too painful for you to feed see the midwife straight away for help. For the first 6 months of life, your baby doesnÆt need anything else but breast milk to keep them healthy and growing strong.', 933, 42, 'EBF/ Breast Care', 1, '2014-07-03 11:09:51', '2014-07-06 16:18:35');
