(147, 'preg-sms-en-47', 1, 'sms', 'English', 'Washing your hands is always very important to prevent worms and sickness for your whole family, but even more important when you have a new baby. New babies will get more sick than older members of your house if exposed to germs from not washing your hands.  Rinsing your hands with water is not enough to get them clean. Wash your hands with soap to remove the germs that can cause infection. Always wash your hands with soap before breast feeding or playing with your baby, after toileting, or cleaning a child that has gone to toilet. Be sure you wash your hands after changing your baby''s nappies.  Also wash hands before and after cooking and before serving food.  Washing your hands with soap and water will go a long way to prevent you, your new baby and your whole house from getting sick or getting worms.', 815, 43, 'Handwashing', 1, '2014-07-03 11:09:51', '2014-07-06 16:18:35'),
(148, 'preg-sms-en-48', 1, 'sms', 'English', 'Immunizations are important for the prevention of many childhood killer diseases. These are polio, tuberculosis, diphtheria, whooping cough, measles, yellow fever, hepatitis B, hemophilus influenza, tetanus, rotavirus, and pneumonia.  Your baby will need some of these immunizations as soon as they are born. Others are needed in the weeks and months after birth.  We will remind you when they are due.  Make sure you keep your baby''s health booklet and take it with you each time you go to clinic.  Immunizations are not harmful and if you have any questions about them be sure to ask the midwife or doctor.', 608, 44, 'Immunizations', 1, '2014-07-03 11:09:51', '2014-07-06 16:18:35');

